ok | author=[[David Sylvester|Sylvester, David]] | title=Magritte | publisher=Abrams | year=1992 | isbn=0-500-09227-3}}\n*{{cite book | author=[[West, Shearer]] | title=The Bullfinch Guide to Art | location=UK | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc | year=1996 | isbn=0-8212-2137-X | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/bulfinchguidetoa0000west }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ren\u00e9 Magritte}}\n*[http://www.magritte.be/ Foundation Magritte]\n*[http://www.all-art.org/art_20th_century/magritte1.html The biography and works of Ren\u00e9 Magritte]\n*[http://www.magrittemuseum.be/ Ren\u00e9 Magritte Museum] in [[Brussels]]\n*{{MoMA artist|3692}}\n*[http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/magritte_rene.html Magritte at Artcyclopedia]\n*[http://www.tate.org.uk/liverpool/exhibitions/renemagritte/default.shtm Ren\u00e9 Magritte: The Pleasure Principle - Exhibition at Tate Liverpool, UK 2011]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081027105849/http://www.fine-arts-museum.be/site/EN/default.asp Mus\u00e9e Magritte Museum] at [[Brussels]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100315011330/http://www.museumchick.com/museum-chick/2010/03/the-mus%C3%A9e-magritte-museum-brussels-surrealism.html A visit to the Mus\u00e9e Magritte Museum]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928060703/http://www.surrealismcentre.ac.uk/publications/papers/journal5/index.htm Patricia Allmer, \"La Reproduction Interdite: Ren\u00e9 Magritte and Forgery\" in ''Papers of Surrealism'', Issue 5, Spring 2007.]\n\n{{Ren\u00e9 Magritte|state=expanded}}\n{{surrealism|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magritte, Rene}}\n[[Category:Ren\u00e9 Magritte| ]]\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lessines]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:Belgian agnostics]]\n[[Category:Belgian artists]]\n[[Category:Surrealist artists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian surrealist artists]]\n[[Category:Walloon people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian painters]]\n[[Category:Burials at Schaerbeek Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts alumni]]\n", "name_user": "94.137.189.212", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Magritte"}
{"title_page": "Redemption (theology)", "text_new": "'''Redemption''' is an essential concept in many religions, including [[Judaism]], [[Christianity]] and [[Islam]]. The [[English language|English]] word \"redemption\" means 'repurchase' or 'buy back'.\n\n==Christianity==\n{{Main|Atonement in Christianity|Salvation in Christianity}}\n{{See also|Redeemer (Christianity)}}\nIn [[Christian theology]], [[Salvation#Redemption|redemption]] (Greek: ''apolutrosis'') refers to the deliverance of [[Christians]] from [[Christian views on sin|sin]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Redeemer, Redemption, 'The New Bible Dictionary'|last=Morris|first=Leon|date=1962|publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]|location=Grand Rapids|pages=1078\u20131079|authorlink=Leon Morris}}</ref> It assumes an important position in [[Salvation in Christianity|salvation]] because the transgressions in question form part of a great system against which human power is helpless.<ref>\"Redemption.\" ''Christian Classics Ethereal Library'' at [[Calvin College]]. July 2, 2009. ''http://www.ccel.org/s/schaff/encyc/encyc09/htm/iv.vii.lxxxv.htm''</ref> [[Leon Morris]] says that \"[[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] uses the concept of redemption primarily to speak of the saving significance of the [[Crucifixion of Jesus|death]] of [[Christ]].\"<ref>{{Cite book |first = Leon |last = Morris |authorlink = Leon Morris |title = 'Redemption' Dictionary of Paul and his Letters |publisher = [[InterVarsity Press]] |date = 1993 |location = Downers Grove |pages = 784}}</ref>  In the [[New Testament]], the redemption word group{{explain|date=June 2018}} is used to refer both to deliverance from sin and freedom from captivity.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Demarest, ''The Cross and Salvation'', 177.</ref>  In Christian theology, redemption is a metaphor for what is achieved through the [[Atonement in Christianity|Atonement]];<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> therefore, there is a [[metaphor]]ical sense in which the death of Jesus pays the price of a ransom, releasing Christians from bondage to sin and death.<ref name=wg>{{Cite book |first = Wayne |last = Grudem |authorlink = Wayne Grudem |title = Systematic Theology: An Introduction to Biblical Doctrine |publisher = [[InterVarsity Press]] |date = 1994 |location = Nottingham |page = 580}}</ref>  \n\nMost evangelical theologians and Protestant denominations reject [[Origen]]'s argument that [[God in Christianity|God]] paid the [[Ransom theory of atonement|ransom price of redemption]] to [[Satan]].<ref name=wg />\n\n==Hinduism==\nA similar concept in [[Indian religions]] is called [[Pr\u0101ya\u015bcitta]], which it is not related to theological sense of sin, but to expiation and personal liberation from guilt or sin.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Lingat |title=The Classical Law of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sauo8iSIj7YC |year=1973 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-01898-3|pages=98\u201399 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Bhikkhu Nyanatusita|title=Analysis of the Bhikkhu Patimokkha|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6s3iBQAAQBAJ |year=2014|publisher=Buddhist Publication Society|isbn=978-955-24-0405-4 |page=86}}</ref>\n\n==Islam==\nIn [[Islam]], redemption is achieved through being a [[Muslim]] and doing no action that would [[Kafir|forfeit]] one's identification with Islam,<ref name=\"Brill Archive\">{{cite book|author1=Hava Lazarus-Yafeh|title=Some Religious Aspects of Islam: A Collection of Articles|date=1981|publisher=Brill Archive|isbn=9789004063297|page=48}}</ref> being of sincere faith (''[[Iman (concept)|iman]]'') and doing virtuous actions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Yahiya Emerick|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Islam, 3rd Edition|date=1 Nov 2011|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781101558812|quote=Salvation and redemption: Islam says our sincere faith and virtuous actions get us into heaven, not just a one-time conversion moment.}}</ref> Muslim sinners need only turn to a merciful God in [[Repentance in Islam|repentance]] and carry out other good deeds, such as prayer (''[[salah]]'') and [[Charity (practice)|charity]], for redemption.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Mahmoud Mustafa Ayoub| authorlink=Mahmoud M. Ayoub |title=The Idea of Redemption in Christianity and Islam|url=http://rsc.byu.edu/archived/selected-articles/idea-redemption-christianity-and-islam|website=BYU|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Chawkat Georges Moucarry|title=Faith to Faith: Christianity & Islam in Dialogue|date=2001|publisher=Inter-Varsity Press|isbn=9780851118994|page=110}}</ref> As a result of this view of redemption, Muslims have criticized alternative views on redemption, especially the [[Christian theology|Christian doctrine]] of [[original sin]].<ref name=\"Brill Archive\"/>\n\n==Judaism==\n{{Main article|Jewish eschatology}}\nIn [[Judaism]], redemption ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] ''ge'ulah'') refers to [[God in Judaism|God]] redeeming the people of [[Israelites|Israel]] from their exiles, starting with that from Egypt.<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Rosh HaShanah, 11b</ref> This includes the [[Jewish eschatology|final redemption]] from the present exile.<ref>for example Talmud Yerushalmi, Tractate Berachot, 2c \"(mid.)</ref>\n\nIn the [[Torah]], redemption referred to the ransom of slaves ([[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 21:8).<ref>{{Cite book |first = Bruce |last = Demarest |authorlink = Bruce Demarest |title = The Cross and Salvation: The Doctrine of Salvation |publisher = [[Crossway Books]] |date = 1997 |location = Wheaton |pages = 176}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of redemption is however a legal and transactional one in the [[Torah]] [[Halakha]], including various sacrifices at the [[Temple in Jerusalem]]:\n* Blood<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Chullin, 35b</ref>\n* Mating<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Moed Katan, 12a</ref>\n* Sales<ref>for example Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Temurah, 31a</ref> and borrowing<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Arachin, 30b</ref>\n* Some specific items like the [[Red Heifer]]<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Shevuot, 11b</ref>\n\nThe concept also applies to redemption of real property such as fields<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Arachin, 14b</ref> and houses,<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Arachin, 33a</ref> stock animals, such as [[donkeys]],<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bechorot, 5b</ref> produce,<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Succah, 40b</ref> and specific items such as [[tefillin]].<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Gittin, 45b</ref> It also means the liberation of an [[estate (law)|estate]] in [[real property]] from a [[mortgage]].\n\nRedemption also applies to individuals or groups: an Israelite slave,<ref>for example Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Kiddushin, 18a</ref> an Israelite captive,<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bava Batra, 8a</ref> and the firstborn son<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bechorot, 31b</ref> ''[[pidyon haben]]'', ({{lang-he|\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05d1\u05df}}) or redemption of the [[Primogeniture|first-born son]],<ref>Eugene Joseph Cohen ''Guide to ritual circumcision and redemption of the first-born son'' Volume 1  - 1984 \"The Redemption of the First-Born - A mother's first-born is to be dedicated to the service of God, in accordance with the verse, \"Sanctify the first-born who opens the womb.\"1 This sanctification was the result of an historical event.\"; Michele Klein ''A Time to Be Born: Customs and Folklore of Jewish Birth'' 2000 Page 224  \"They have attributed healing properties to the stick.54 REDEMPTION OF THE FIRST-BORN SON A first child has special significance for both parents, and this was as true in biblical times as today, but then only when the child was male\";  Mark Washofsky ''Jewish living: a guide to contemporary reform practice'' 2001 Page 148 \"Redemption of the First-born Son (Pidyon Haben)- In Jewish tradition, the first-born son is to be \"redeemed\" from God. This originates in the belief that God \"acquired\" the Israelite first-born by sparing them from makkat bekhorot,\" ;  Ruth Langer ''To Worship To Worship God Properly: Tensions Between Liturgical Custom and Halakhah in Judaism (Monographs of the Hebrew Union College Series) 2005 Page 73 \"Redemption of the First Born.\"</ref> is a [[mitzvah]] in [[Judaism]] whereby a Jewish firstborn son is redeemed from God by use of [[silver coin]]s to a [[kohen]].<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bechorot, 51b</ref> It is from these three cases that the concept of exilic redemption is derived because the People Israel are considered God's 'firstborn' derived from [[Jacob]], who are God's slaves<ref>Vayikra 25:55</ref> forever, but are currently held captive, even while they reside in the modern state of [[Israel]].\n\nIn [[Hasidic philosophy]] parallels are drawn between the redemption from exile and the personal redemption achieved when a person refines his character traits, although there is no source for this in the Talmud. Rather the Messianic redemption is linked to observing [[Shabbat]],<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Shabbat, 118b</ref> [[Jewish prayer]],<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Berachot, 4b</ref> and the promise of redemption for those looking toward [[Mount Zion]],<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Ketubot, 75a</ref> the last being the original cultural source of '[[Zionism]]'. As such, the original intent of Zionism was the redemption process by which the [[Land of Israel]] that has been pledged to the [[Israelites]]<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bava Batra, 119a</ref> is reclaimed, accomplished through a payment of the debt owed to God<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> as a fulfillment of the conditions set out in the [[Torah]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [[Baptism]]\n* [[Easter]]\n* [[Good Friday]]\n* [[Karma]]\n* [[Penitence]]\n* [[Salvation]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00548vp Redemption], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Richard Harries, Janet Soskice and Stephen Mulhall (''In Our Time'', Mar. 13, 2003)\n\n{{Christian Soteriology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redemption (Theology)}}\n[[Category:Salvation]]\n[[Category:Religious terminology]]\n", "text_old": "'''Redemption''' is an essential concept in many religions, including [[Judaism]], [[Christianity]] and [[Islam]]. The [[English language|English]] word \"redemption\" means 'repurchase' or 'buy back'.\n\n==Christianity==\n{{Main|Atonement in Christianity|Salvation in Christianity}}\n{{See also|Redeemer (Christianity)}}\nIn [[Christian theology]], [[Salvation#Redemption|redemption]] (Greek: ''apolutrosis'') refers to the deliverance of [[Christians]] from [[Christian views on sin|sin]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Redeemer, Redemption, 'The New Bible Dictionary'|last=Morris|first=Leon|date=1962|publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]|location=Grand Rapids|pages=1078\u20131079|authorlink=Leon Morris}}</ref> It assumes an important position in [[Salvation in Christianity|salvation]] because the transgressions in question form part of a great system against which human power is helpless.<ref>\"Redemption.\" ''Christian Classics Ethereal Library'' at [[Calvin College]]. July 2, 2009. ''http://www.ccel.org/s/schaff/encyc/encyc09/htm/iv.vii.lxxxv.htm''</ref> [[Leon Morris]] says that \"[[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] uses the concept of redemption primarily to speak of the saving significance of the [[Crucifixion of Jesus|death]] of [[Christ]].\"<ref>{{Cite book |first = Leon |last = Morris |authorlink = Leon Morris |title = 'Redemption' Dictionary of Paul and his Letters |publisher = [[InterVarsity Press]] |date = 1993 |location = Downers Grove |pages = 784}}</ref>  In the [[New Testament]], the redemption word group{{explain|date=June 2018}} is used to refer both to deliverance from sin and freedom from captivity.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Demarest, ''The Cross and Salvation'', 177.</ref>  In Christian theology, redemption is a metaphor for what is achieved through the [[Atonement in Christianity|Atonement]];<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> therefore, there is a [[metaphor]]ical sense in which the death of Jesus pays the price of a ransom, releasing Christians from bondage to sin and death.<ref name=wg>{{Cite book |first = Wayne |last = Grudem |authorlink = Wayne Grudem |title = Systematic Theology: An Introduction to Biblical Doctrine |publisher = [[InterVarsity Press]] |date = 1994 |location = Nottingham |page = 580}}</ref>  \n\nMost evangelical theologians and Protestant denominations reject [[Origen]]'s argument that [[God in Christianity|God]] paid the [[Ransom theory of atonement|ransom price of redemption]] to [[Satan]].<ref name=wg />\n\n==Hinduism==\nA similar concept in [[Indian religions]] is called [[Pr\u0101ya\u015bcitta]], which it is not related to theological sense of sin, but to expiation and personal liberation from guilt or sin.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Lingat |title=The Classical Law of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sauo8iSIj7YC |year=1973 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-01898-3|pages=98\u201399 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Bhikkhu Nyanatusita|title=Analysis of the Bhikkhu Patimokkha|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6s3iBQAAQBAJ |year=2014|publisher=Buddhist Publication Society|isbn=978-955-24-0405-4 |page=86}}</ref>\n\n==Islam==\nIn [[Islam]], redemption is achieved through being a [[Muslim]] and doing no action that would [[Kafir|forfeit]] one's identification with Islam,<ref name=\"Brill Archive\">{{cite book|author1=Hava Lazarus-Yafeh|title=Some Religious Aspects of Islam: A Collection of Articles|date=1981|publisher=Brill Archive|isbn=9789004063297|page=48}}</ref> being of sincere faith (''[[Iman (concept)|iman]]'') and doing virtuous actions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Yahiya Emerick|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Islam, 3rd Edition|date=1 Nov 2011|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781101558812|quote=Salvation and redemption: Islam says our sincere faith and virtuous actions get us into heaven, not just a one-time conversion moment.}}</ref> Muslim sinners need only turn to a merciful God in [[Repentance in Islam|repentance]] and carry out other good deeds, such as prayer (''[[salah]]'') and [[Charity (practice)|charity]], for redemption.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Mahmoud Mustafa Ayoub| authorlink=Mahmoud M. Ayoub |title=The Idea of Redemption in Christianity and Islam|url=http://rsc.byu.edu/archived/selected-articles/idea-redemption-christianity-and-islam|website=BYU|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Chawkat Georges Moucarry|title=Faith to Faith: Christianity & Islam in Dialogue|date=2001|publisher=Inter-Varsity Press|isbn=9780851118994|page=110}}</ref> As a result of this view of redemption, Muslims have criticized alternative views on redemption, especially the [[Christian theology|Christian doctrine]] of [[original sin]].<ref name=\"Brill Archive\"/>\n\n==Judaism==\n{{Main article|Jewish eschatology}}\nIn [[Judaism]], redemption ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] ''ge'ulah'') refers to [[God in Judaism|God]] redeeming the people of [[Israelites|Israel]] from their exiles, starting with that from Egypt.<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Rosh HaShanah, 11b</ref> This includes the [[Jewish eschatology|final redemption]] from the present exile.<ref>for example Talmud Yerushalmi, Tractate Berachot, 2c \"(mid.)</ref>\n\nIn the [[Torah]], redemption referred to the ransom of slaves ([[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 21:8).<ref>{{Cite book |first = Bruce |last = Demarest |authorlink = Bruce Demarest |title = The Cross and Salvation: The Doctrine of Salvation |publisher = [[Crossway Books]] |date = 1997 |location = Wheaton |pages = 176}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of redemption is however a legal and transactional one in the [[Torah]] [[Halakha]], including various sacrifices at the [[Temple in Jerusalem]]:\n* Blood <ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Chullin, 35b</ref>\n* Mating <ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Moed Katan, 12a</ref>\n* Sales <ref>for example Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Temurah, 31a</ref> and borrowing <ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Arachin, 30b</ref>\n* Some specific items like the [[Red Heifer]] <ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Shevuot, 11b</ref>\n\nThe concept also applies to redemption of real property such as fields <ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Arachin, 14b</ref> and houses,<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Arachin, 33a</ref> stock animals, such as [[donkeys]],<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bechorot, 5b</ref> produce,<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Succah, 40b</ref> and specific items such as [[tefillin]].<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Gittin, 45b</ref> It also means the liberation of an [[estate (law)|estate]] in [[real property]] from a [[mortgage]].\n\nRedemption also applies to individuals or groups: an Israelite slave,<ref>for example Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Kiddushin, 18a</ref> an Israelite captive,<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bava Batra, 8a</ref> and the firstborn son<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bechorot, 31b</ref> ''[[pidyon haben]]'', ({{lang-he|\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05d1\u05df}}) or redemption of the [[Primogeniture|first-born son]],<ref>Eugene Joseph Cohen ''Guide to ritual circumcision and redemption of the first-born son'' Volume 1  - 1984 \"The Redemption of the First-Born - A mother's first-born is to be dedicated to the service of God, in accordance with the verse, \"Sanctify the first-born who opens the womb.\"1 This sanctification was the result of an historical event.\"; Michele Klein ''A Time to Be Born: Customs and Folklore of Jewish Birth'' 2000 Page 224  \"They have attributed healing properties to the stick.54 REDEMPTION OF THE FIRST-BORN SON A first child has special significance for both parents, and this was as true in biblical times as today, but then only when the child was male\";  Mark Washofsky ''Jewish living: a guide to contemporary reform practice'' 2001 Page 148 \"Redemption of the First-born Son (Pidyon Haben)- In Jewish tradition, the first-born son is to be \"redeemed\" from God. This originates in the belief that God \"acquired\" the Israelite first-born by sparing them from makkat bekhorot,\" ;  Ruth Langer ''To Worship To Worship God Properly: Tensions Between Liturgical Custom and Halakhah in Judaism (Monographs of the Hebrew Union College Series) 2005 Page 73 \"Redemption of the First Born.\"</ref> is a [[mitzvah]] in [[Judaism]] whereby a Jewish firstborn son is redeemed from God by use of [[silver coin]]s to a [[kohen]].<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bechorot, 51b</ref> It is from these three cases that the concept of exilic redemption is derived because the People Israel are considered God's 'firstborn' derived from [[Jacob]], who are God's slaves <ref>Vayikra 25:55</ref> forever, but are currently held captive, even while they reside in the modern state of [[Israel]].\n\nIn [[Hasidic philosophy]] parallels are drawn between the redemption from exile and the personal redemption achieved when a person refines his character traits, although there is no source for this in the Talmud. Rather the Messianic redemption is linked to observing [[Shabbat]],<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Shabbat, 118b</ref> [[Jewish prayer]],<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Berachot, 4b</ref> and the promise of redemption for those looking toward [[Mount Zion]],<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Ketubot, 75a</ref> the last being the original cultural source of '[[Zionism]]'. As such, the original intent of Zionism was the redemption process by which the [[Land of Israel]] that has been pledged to the [[Israelites]]<ref>Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Bava Batra, 119a</ref> is reclaimed, accomplished through a payment of the debt owed to God<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> as a fulfillment of the conditions set out in the [[Torah]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [[Baptism]]\n* [[Easter]]\n* [[Good Friday]]\n* [[Karma]]\n* [[Penitence]]\n* [[Salvation]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00548vp Redemption], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Richard Harries, Janet Soskice and Stephen Mulhall (''In Our Time'', Mar. 13, 2003)\n\n{{Christian Soteriology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redemption (Theology)}}\n[[Category:Salvation]]\n[[Category:Religious terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Jessicapierce", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor copy edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redemption_(theology)"}
{"title_page": "Gateway of India", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Short description|Arch-monument in Mumbai, India}}\n{{Distinguish|text = the [[India Gate]],  the World War I war memorial in New Delhi}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox building\n| building_name       = Gateway of India\n| native_building_name= \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     =\n| image               = Mumbai 03-2016 30 Gateway of India.jpg\n| caption             = \n| map_type            = India Mumbai#India Maharashtra#India \n| building_type       = [[Triumphal arch]]\n| architectural_style = [[Indo-Saracenic]]\n| structural_system   =\n| cost                = {{INR}}21 lakhs\n| ren_cost            =\n| location            = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| address             =\n| owner               = [[Archaeological Survey of India]]\n|coordinates     = {{coord|18.9219|72.8346|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption     = Location of Gateway of India in Maharashtra\n| start_date          = 31 March 1913\n| completion_date     = 1924\n| inauguration_date   = 4 December 1924\n| renovation_date     =\n| height              = {{convert|26|m|ft|abbr=on|0}}\n| diameter            = {{convert|15|m|ft|0|abbr=off}}\n| other_dimensions    =\n| floor_area          =\n| main_contractor     =\n| architect           = [[George Wittet]]\n| architecture_firm   = [[Gammon India]]\n| structural_engineer =\n| services_engineer   =\n| civil_engineer      =\n| other_designers     =\n| quantity_surveyor   =\n| awards              =\n| ren_architect       = George Wittet\n| website             = [https://gatewayofindia.org gatewayofindia.org]\n| ren_firm            =\n| ren_str_engineer    =\n| ren_serv_engineer   =\n| ren_civ_engineer    =\n| ren_oth_designers   =\n| ren_qty_surveyor    =\n| ren_awards          =\n| references          =\n}}\n\nThe '''Gateway of India''' is an arch-monument built in the early twentieth century in the city of [[Mumbai]], in the [[India]]n state of [[Maharashtra]]. It was erected to commemorate the landing in December 1911 at [[Apollo Bunder]], Mumbai (then Bombay) of [[Emperor of India|King-Emperor]] [[George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen-Empress Mary]], the first British monarchs to visit India. At the time of the royal visit, the gateway was not yet built, and a cardboard structure greeted the monarch. The foundation stone was laid in March 1913 for a monument built in the [[Indo-Saracenic]] style, incorporating elements of 16th-century Marathi architecture. The final design of the monument by architect [[George Wittet]] was sanctioned only in 1914, and construction was completed in 1924. The structure is a [[triumphal arch]] made of [[basalt]], which is {{convert|26|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} high.\n\nAfter its construction the gateway was used as a symbolic ceremonial entrance to British India for important colonial personnel. It has been called a symbol of \"conquest and colonisation\" commemorating British colonial legacy. The gateway is also the monument from where the last British troops left India in 1948, following Indian independence. It is located on the waterfront at an angle, opposite the [[The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel|Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel]] and overlooks the [[Arabian Sea]]. Today, the monument is synonymous with the city of Mumbai, and is amongst its prime tourist attractions. The gateway is also a gathering spot for locals, street vendors, and photographers soliciting services. It holds significance for the local Jewish community as it has been the spot for [[Hanukkah]] celebrations, with the lighting of the [[Menorah (Hanukkah)|menorah]], since 2003. There are five jetties located at the gateway, of which two are used for commercial ferry operations.\n\nThe gateway was the site of a [[25 August 2003 Mumbai bombings|terror attack in August 2003]], when there was a bomb blast in a taxi parked in front of it. Access to the gateway was restricted after people congregated at its premises following the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|2008 Mumbai terror attacks]], in which the Taj Hotel opposite the gateway and other locations in its vicinity were targeted.\n\nIn March 2019, the Maharashtra state government proposed a four-step plan to develop the location for the convenience of tourists, following a direction issued by the state governor in February 2019.\n\n==History and significance==\n{{multiple image|perrow=1/1|total_width=200|| align=left|caption_align=left\n| image1 = Gateway of India, Bombay. 1911.JPG|caption1=The gateway, in 1924\n| image2 = Departure of British Troops from India - 28 February 1948 - Gateway of India.jpg|caption2=Departure of the last British troops from the gateway, in 1948}}\nThe gateway was built to commemorate the arrival of George V, Emperor of India and Mary of Teck, Empress consort, in India at Apollo Bunder, Mumbai (then Bombay) on 2 December 1911 prior to the [[Delhi Durbar|Delhi Durbar of 1911]]; it was the first visit of a British monarch to India.{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}}{{sfn|Anthony Hewitt|1993|p=173}}{{sfn|Timothy H. Parsons|2014|p=3}} However, they only got to see a cardboard model of the monument,{{efn-ua|group=note|While Dup\u00e9e (2008) notes that the king and queen passed through a \"temporarily constructed mock cardboard and [[pastiche]] structure\",{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}} de Bruyn et al. (2008) note the same simply as a \"fake cardboard structure\"{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2008|p=92}}.}} as construction did not begin until 1915.{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}}{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=92}} The foundation stone for the gateway was laid on 31 March 1913 by then governor of Bombay, [[Sir George Sydenham Clarke]] with the final design of [[George Wittet]] for the gateway sanctioned in August 1914.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra1999|p=42}}{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=92}} Before the gateway's construction, Apollo Bunder used to serve a native fishing ground.{{sfn|Gillian Tindall|1992|p=6-7}} Between 1915 and 1919 work continued at the Apollo Bunder to reclaim the land on which the gateway was to be built, along with the construction of a sea wall.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra1999|p=42}} [[Gammon India]] had undertaken construction work for the gateway.{{sfn|Renu Saran|2014|loc = ch. on 'Gateway of India}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Gammon India claims to have done India's first pre-cast reinforced concrete piling for the foundations of the gateway.{{sfn|B. Karunakar|2011|loc= ch. on 'Gammon India Ltd.'}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gammonindia.com/projects/landmark-project-for-gammon-india.htm |title=Landmark Projects |website=www.gammonindia.com |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219044719/http://www.gammonindia.com/projects/landmark-project-for-gammon-india.htm |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} Its foundations were completed in 1920 while construction was finished in 1924.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1995|p=118}}{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra1999|p=42}} The gateway was opened to the public on 4 December 1924 by then viceroy, [[Rufus Isaacs, 1st Marquess of Reading]].{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1995}} Following Indian independence, the last British troops to leave India, the First Battalion of the [[Somerset Light Infantry]], passed through the gateway with a 21-gun salute, as part of a ceremony on 28 February 1948, signalling the end of the [[British Raj]].{{sfn|Robert W. Bradnock|1994}}{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Morris (2005) writes about the gateway, \"This was where the British landed: and this where, in the end, they left. The Gateway of India did not see many ceremonial arrivals after all, during its three decades under British rule, but it formed the background to one historical departure \u2014 the last parade with which, in 1947, the British said goodbye to their Indian Empire.\"{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}}}\n\nN. Kamala, professor at [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jnu.ac.in/content/nkamala |title=N. Kamala |website=jnu.ac.in |publisher=Jawaharlal Nehru University |access-date=19 September 2019}}</ref> refers to the gateway as a \"jewel in the crown\" and a \"symbol of conquest and colonisation\".{{sfn|SimonSt-Pierre|2000|p=245|loc=chpt. 13}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Kamala (2000) writes, \"Through the Gateway, the imperial traveller could perceive in his mind's eye the vision of a subject-nation, a nation constructed and processed in and for his gaze. As Tejaswini Niranjana points out, one of the professed aims of English education was to give the colonized, \"along with the English language, models of national culture\" (1992, 107),{{sfn|Tejaswini Niranjana|1992|p=107}} the stated objectives being to \"give a liberal English education to the middle and upper classes, in order that we may furnish them with both the materials and models for the formation of a national literature\" (Trevelyan 1838, 175).{{sfn|Charles Edward Trevelyan|1838|p=175}} While various notions of India\u2014indeed, various Indias\u2014may have pre-existed British colonization, this one monolithic nation, India, was constructed only in English translation. The Gateway of India looked outward, welcoming the colonizer, a symbol and facilitator of appropriation, but it also looked inward, bringing a people together (and driving them apart) as they dutifully defined their nation in the curiously perceived neutrality of the English language.\"{{sfn|SimonSt-Pierre|2000|p=245|loc=chpt. 13}}}} The monument commemorates the legacy of British colonial rule, namely the first visit of a British monarch to India and its use as an entry point for prominent colonial personnel into British India.{{sfn|SimonSt-Pierre|2000|p=245}} Today the gateway is synonymous with the city of Mumbai.<ref name = \"deccan\" /><ref name=\"Kulkarni\"/>{{efn-ua|group=note|The gateway has also been featured in films shot in or with stories based in Mumbai. Ranjani Mazumdar (2010), referring to the 1989 Indian film ''[[Parinda]]'', writes, \"In a city where the rich and poor live cheek by jowl, where disenchantment is the experience of the majority, Mumbai Noir has become synonymous with urban decay, crime, claustrophobia, and an assortment of characters marked by some sort of death wish...Karan is soon sucked into a vortex of violence in a narrative that consciously uses Mumbai's familiar locations like the Gateway of India, the Babulnath Temple, the fountains and various abandoned factories...Urban space is not just the backdrop but a central character in the film and the use of the Gateway of India to stage a bloody climax paved the way for a new imagination of violence.\"{{sfn|Helio San Miguel|2012|loc= chpt. on 'Mumbai Noir'}}<br/>There is also a 1957 Indian film titled ''Gateway of India'' featuring the monument, starring [[Madhubala]] and [[Om Prakash]].{{sfn|Deepa Gahlot2015|loc=chpt. on 'Gateway of India (1957)'}}}} Since its construction, the gateway has remained amongst the first structures visible to visitors arriving in Bombay by the sea.{{sfn|Chatterji, Monojit|1997|pp=233-234}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Tindall (1992) writes, \"If Bombay is, as some think, an Indian city with a Western fa\u00e7ade, then the Gateway and the Taj{{efn-ua|group=note|Referring to the [[The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel|Taj Mahal Palace Hotel]] located opposite the gateway, both visible together from the sea.}} are this fa\u00e7ade in spite of their determinedly oriental opulence.\"{{sfn|Gillian Tindall|1992|p=12}} While Dup\u00e9e (2008) writes, \"The city's dramatical imperial arch graced the harbor's approach, lending substance to the characterization that Bombay was the \"gateway\" or \"front door\" to the subcontinent, not unlike, according to one author, the [[Arc de Triomphe]]'s as entryway into the city of [[Paris]]...The arch of honey-colored basalt was not completed until 1924, but once erected it became for travellers the city's dominant architectural icon. The Taj Mahal Hotel, situated nearby, also faced the harbour, commanding a stunning view of the sea and, dependent upon the traveller's aesthetic tastes, lending an imposing grandeur to the city's image.\"{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}} Yet Monojit (1997) notes, \"Visible from way out at sea, it was the first sight of normality in what was to be an alien land...Today, the Gateway is a favourite promenade spot for thousands of Bomabyites...the Gateway that once symbolised Imperial rule still symbolises the city's closeness to the West, its contact with the outside world.\"{{sfn|Chatterji, Monojit|1997|p=233}}}}\n\nSince 2003, the gateway has been the location for the local Jewish community to light the menorah for Hanukkah celebrations every year.<ref name=\"hanukkah\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://religionnews.com/2018/12/14/photos-of-the-week-52/ | title=Photos of the Week | date=14 December 2018 | newspaper=Religion News Service | accessdate=16 August 2019 | author=Doyle, Kit | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171233/https://religionnews.com/2018/12/14/photos-of-the-week-52/ | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> This ritual was started by [[Gavriel Holtzberg|Rabbi Gavriel Noach Holtzberg]] of the chabad in Mumbai (located in [[Nariman House]]).<ref name=\"hanukkah\">{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/hanukkah-lights-up-at-gateway-of-india-with-a-wish-to-spread-light-and-love/ | title=Hanukkah lights up at Gateway of India, with a wish to spread light and love | newspaper=Indian Express | date=21 December 2014 | accessdate=16 August 2019 | author=Iyer, Kavitha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171256/https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/hanukkah-lights-up-at-gateway-of-india-with-a-wish-to-spread-light-and-love/ | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It also became a site for prayers following the 2008 Mumbai terror attacks which targeted, amongst others, Nariman House.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/baby-moshe-s-grandparents-in-mumbai-to-conduct-prayers/story-6EZOIHtEqO8s5KpQ3Zpb1K.html | title=Baby Moshe's grandparents in Mumbai, to conduct prayers | date=25 December 2008 | newspaper=Hindustan Times | accessdate=16 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171231/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/baby-moshe-s-grandparents-in-mumbai-to-conduct-prayers/story-6EZOIHtEqO8s5KpQ3Zpb1K.html | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Rabbi Holtzberg lost his life in the 2008 terror attacks.<ref name = \"hanukkah\"/>\n\n==Design and architecture==\n[[File:Gateway of India inscriptions.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Inscription on the gateway reading: \"Erected to commemorate the landing in India of their Imperial Majesties King George V and Queen Mary on the Second of December MCMXI\"]]\nThe gateway's arch has a height of {{convert|26|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} with its central dome being {{convert|15|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} in diameter.{{sfn|P. K. Agrawal|loc=chpt. on ' Gateway of India}}{{sfn|Renu Saran|2014|loc=ch. on 'Gateway of India}} The monument is built of yellow basalt and reinforced concrete.{{sfn|Melody S. Mis|2004|p=42}} The stones were sourced locally while the perforated screens were brought in from [[Gwalior]].{{sfn|Jagir Singh BajwaRavinder Kaur|2007|p=240}} The monument faces towards the Mumbai Harbour.{{sfn|Sarina Singh|2010|pp=783-784}} There are four turrets on the structure of the gateway, and there are steps constructed behind the arch of the gateway which lead to the Arabian Sea.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{Britannica|72526|Mumbai - Cultural Life|Chakravarthi Raghavan}}</ref> The monument features intricate stone [[latticework]] (also known as the ''[[jali]]'' work).{{sfn|P. K. Agrawal|loc=chpt. on ' Gateway of India}} The Scottish architect, [[George Wittet]] combined elements of the [[Roman triumphal arch]] and 16th-century architecture of Gujarat.{{sfn|Shobhna Gupta2003|p=111}}{{efn-ua|group=note| Bandyopadhyay et al. (2008) write, \"The Indian government's efforts in this portrayal of the Hindu heritage is nowhere more prominent than the mention of the Gateway of India architecture in Mumbai...it was stressed that though the British rulers designed the Gateway, it was according to the Gujarat (one of the Indian states) style.\"{{sfn|Bandyopadhyay, Ranjan|2008|p=801}}}} The architecture also combines indigenous architectural elements with elements of Islamic architecture, known as the Indo-Saracenic.{{sfn|Kirpal Sigh Annie Mathew|p=8}} The harbour front was realigned in order to make an esplanade, which would sweep down to the centre of the town. On each side of the arch, there are large halls with the capacity to hold 600 people.{{sfn|Melody S. Mis|2004|p=42}} The cost of the construction was {{INR}}21 lakhs (two million one hundred thousand rupees), borne by the then government.{{sfn|Renu Saran|2014|loc=ch. on 'Gateway of India}} Due to a paucity of funds, the approach road was never built. Hence, the gateway stands at an angle to the road leading up to it.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1995}}\n\nIn February 2019, Seagate Technology and CyArk embarked on a mission to digitally record and preserve the gateway, by digital scanning and archiving of the monument.<ref name = \"deccan\"/> The images and data collected will be used to make photo-real three dimensional models.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/putting-the-gateway-on-the-cloud/article26334296.ece | title=Digitally recreating the Gateway of India | date=22 February 2019 | newspaper=The Hindu | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Karangutkar, Suyash}}</ref> This is a part of CyArk's international programme for digitally preserving heritage monuments.<ref name=\"deccan\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/gateway-india-be-digitally-719577.html | title=Gateway of India to be digitally preserved | date=21 February 2019 | newspaper=Deccan Herald | accessdate=13 August 2019 | author=Bose, Mrityunjay | location=Mumbai | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813105317/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/gateway-india-be-digitally-719577.html | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It involves aerial surveys conducted with terrestrial laser scanning (LiDAR), drones and [[photogrammetry]] exercises.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://cio.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/corporate-news/seagate-partners-with-cyark-to-digitally-preserve-the-gateway-of-india/68095055 | title=Seagate partners with CyArk to digitally preserve the Gateway of India | date=21 February 2019 | newspaper=Economic TImes | accessdate=14 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814071353/https://cio.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/corporate-news/seagate-partners-with-cyark-to-digitally-preserve-the-gateway-of-india/68095055 | archive-date=14 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The drawings and three-dimensional models will inform any future reconstruction works.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/pvt-firms-scan-every-square-cm-of-gateway-of-india-to-digitally-preserve-the-monument/articleshow/68100647.cms | title=Pvt firms scan every square cm of Gateway of India to 'digitally preserve' the monument | date=21 February 2019 | newspaper=The Times of India | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Jaisinghani, Bella | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731043311/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/pvt-firms-scan-every-square-cm-of-gateway-of-india-to-digitally-preserve-the-monument/articleshow/68100647.cms | archive-date=31 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Location and jetties==\n[[File:Emperor of Maratha India.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Statue of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj, in the vicinity of the gateway]]\nThe gateway stands at an angle, opposite to the Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel, which was built in 1903.{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=125}} In the grounds of the gateway, opposite the monument, stands the statue of [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj]], the [[Maratha]] warrior-hero who fought against the [[Mughal empire]] to establish the [[Maratha empire]] in the 17th century.{{sfn|Berlitz|2017}}{{sfn|B.K. Chaturvedi|2002|p=146}} The statue was unveiled on 26 January 1961 on the occasion of India's [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]].{{sfn|Bombay Civic Journal|1975|p=59}}{{sfn|Civic Affairs|1961|p=91}} It replaced a bronze statue of King-Emperor George V which stood at its place.{{sfn|Bombay Civic Journal|1975|p=39}}{{sfn|Civic Affairs|1961|p=86}}{{efn-ua|group=note|McGarr (2015) writes, \"In July 1959, in Bombay, moves were set in train to replace a statue of George V, which stood next to the Gateway of India on the city\u2019s waterfront, with a \ufb01gure of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj, a renowned Maratha warrior. As one of the best-known royal statues in India, the decision elicited strong feelings among those on both sides of the statues debate. One British expatriate living in Bombay, wrote to the editor of ''[[The Times of India]]'' to decry \u2018the limits [to] which petty-mindedness and nationalistic feeling can be carried\u2019. Back in London, [[William Haley]], editor of ''[[The Times]]'', echoed such sentiment...Haley wrote to a friend, \u2018this business of removing statues is really rather nonsense. Rather like un-writing history in [[George Orwell]]\u2019s ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four|1984]]''. What is done is done and there is no reason for the Indians to be ashamed of it...When will man-kind grow up?\u2019 Of\ufb01cial Indian sentiment, however, had begun to turn decisively against the retention of British statues in public locations. In September 1961, in Maharashtra (a new state carved from the former [[Bombay presidency]] along linguistic lines) a committee established to look into the retention of British monuments reported that none of the state\u2019s British statues could be regarded as offensive to Indian nationalism, and extremely few had been defaced. Nonetheless, the committee recommended the progressive replacement of British iconography with that \u2018more in consonance with the sense of patriotism and nationalism which has developed since the attainment of Independence in 1947\u2019...In [[Calcutta]], municipal authorities announced that statues of Lord Lawrence and [[Queen Victoria]], which stood in prominent positions in the heart of the city, would be replaced by \ufb01gures of the Indian nationalist icons...Only in [[New Delhi]], it seemed, was a nationwide trend towards the removal of British statuary. The continued presence of British iconography in India\u2019s capital was shortly, however, to become a matter of contentious political debate.\"{{sfn|McGarr, Paul M.|2015|p=814}}}} In 2016, ''[[Mid Day]]'' reported that the George V statue is kept locked in a tin shed belonging to the [[Central_Public_Works_Department#State_Public_Works_Departments_in_India|Public Works Department]], behind [[Elphinstone College]], in [[Fort (Mumbai precinct)|Fort]], Mumbai.<ref name=\"georgepancham\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/mumbai-sculptors-kin-seek-to-save-king-george-v-from-shabby-pwd-shed/17111153 |title=Mumbai: Sculptor's kin seek to save King George V from shabby PWD shed |last=Puranik |first=Apoorva |date=7 April 2016 |work=Mid Day |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170726130633/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/mumbai-sculptors-kin-seek-to-save-king-george-v-from-shabby-pwd-shed/17111153 |archive-date=26 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The George V statue was sculpted by G. K. Mhatre,{{sfn|A. K. Bag|2001|p=83}}{{sfn|Bombay State Road Transport Corporation|1958|p=36}} who has over 300 sculptures to his credit in India.<ref name=\"georgepancham\"/> Hemant Pathare, Mhatre's great-grandson and Sandeep Dahisarkar, a historian, researcher, and academician, have made efforts to relocate the George V statue to a museum, the latter of whom has reasserted the statue as ''[[Swadeshi_movement#Etymology|swadeshi]]'' art.<ref name=\"georgepancham\"/> The other statue in the locality of the gateway is that of [[Swami Vivekananda]],{{sfn|Ajoy Kumar Sen1991|p=320}}{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1999|p=47}} an Indian monk who is credited as a key figure in the introduction of Indian philosophies such as [[Vedanta]] and [[Yoga]] to the west, and with bringing [[Hinduism]] to the status of a major world religion during the late 19th century.{{sfn|Narasingha Prosad Sil|1997}}{{efn-ua|group=note| Bandyopadhyay et al. (2008), referring to the renaming of colonial names of cities and locations, write, \"...although the Gateway is associated with colonial heritage, which the Indian government also embraces, it wants to make a point that the Hindus were not short of renowned leaders/personalities (here in the case of two statues, Swami Vivekananda who is arguably India's greatest spiritual celebrity, and Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj who was arguably one of the country's most respected Hindu rulers). This resistance, it can be argued is targeted in opposition to the Western colonial influence which...is a \"psychological state resulting from suppressed feelings of envy and hatred.\"{{sfn|Bandyopadhyay, Ranjan|2008|p=801}}<br/>In 2017, [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] member [[Raj K. Purohit]], who has held six terms in the [[Maharashtra Legislative Assembly]], demanded the gateway to be renamed \"Bharat Dwaar\" (the [[Hindi language|Hindi]] translation of \"the gateway of India\") to ensure an \"Indian name\" for the monument and to let go of India's \"colonial hangover\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/bjp-mla-in-mumbai-wants-gateway-of-india-renamed-to-bharatdwar/story-33HkO0fsmxDjx4i996WOuL.html |title=BJP MLA in Mumbai wants Gateway of India renamed to 'Bharatdwar' |last=Rawal |first=Swapnil |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=11 June 2017 |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113012322/https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/bjp-mla-in-mumbai-wants-gateway-of-india-renamed-to-bharatdwar/story-33HkO0fsmxDjx4i996WOuL.html |archive-date=13 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He further claimed the monument to be a \"symbol of slavery\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/617331/rename-gateway-india-bharat-dwaar.html | title=Rename Gateway of India as Bharat Dwaar: BJP MLA | date=14 June 2017 | accessdate=23 September 2019 | newspaper=Deccan Herald | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620035939/https://www.deccanherald.com/content/617331/rename-gateway-india-bharat-dwaar.html | archive-date=20 June 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\nThere are five jetties located around the monument.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/mumbaiterrorstrike/Story.aspx?ID=NEWEN20090081499&type=News |title=Gateway of India jetties to move location |last=Thakkar |first=Dharmesh |date=27 January 2009 |newspaper=NDTV |access-date=30 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212011149/http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/mumbaiterrorstrike/Story.aspx?ID=NEWEN20090081499&type=News |archive-date=12 February 2011}}</ref> The first jetty is exclusive to the [[Bhabha Atomic Research Centre]], while the second and third are used for commercial ferry operations, the fourth one is closed, and the fifth is exclusive to the [[Royal Bombay Yacht Club]].{{sfn|DK Travel|2014|p=450}} The second and third jetties are the starting point for tourists to reach the [[Elephanta Caves]], which are fifty minutes away by boat from the monument.{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=125}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-heritage-week-revisiting-a-lost-culture-in-the-city-of-caves_1677368 |title=Mumbai heritage week: Revisiting a lost culture in the city of caves |date=18 April 2012 |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis |access-date=18 April 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627181825/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-heritage-week-revisiting-a-lost-culture-in-the-city-of-caves_1677368 |archive-date=27 June 2012}}</ref> Other routes from the gateway include ferry rides to [[Rewas]], [[Mandwa, Maharashtra|Mandwa]] and [[Alibaug]], while cruises also operate from the gateway.<ref name=dna09/> These ferries reportedly carry an overload of daily passengers.<ref name=\"md11\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mid-day.com/news/2011/oct/021011-Disaster-floats-at-gateway.htm |title=Disaster floats at gateway |date=2 October 2011 |newspaper=Mid Day |access-date=30 April 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308164442/http://www.mid-day.com/news/2011/oct/021011-Disaster-floats-at-gateway.htm |archive-date=8 March 2012}}</ref> The [[Mumbai Port Trust]] licenses vessels to use the gateway while the [[Maharashtra Maritime Board]] issues fitness certificates to them.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/jetty-off-nariman-point-to-give-easier-access-to-proposed-mid-sea-shivaji-memorial/story-aA7xOtuHZFmzrWwg9XY9jO.html |title=Jetty off Nariman Point to give easier access to proposed mid-sea Shivaji Memorial |last=Rawal |first=Swapnil |date=1 November 2018 |newspaper=Hindustan Times |access-date=20 September 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190917194350/https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/jetty-off-nariman-point-to-give-easier-access-to-proposed-mid-sea-shivaji-memorial/story-aA7xOtuHZFmzrWwg9XY9jO.html |archive-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism and development==\n[[File:WNC personnel cleaning the premises of the Gateway of India on World Environment Day 2015.JPG|thumb|right|200px|[[Western Naval Command]] personnel participating in a cleaning drive at the gateway, on occasion of World Environment Day in 2015]]\nThe gateway is amongst the prime tourist attractions in Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/education-today/gk-current-affairs/story/gateway-of-india-9-facts-you-should-know-1402083-2018-12-04 | title=Gateway of India: 9 facts you should know | publisher=India Today | date=4 December 2018 | accessdate=15 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815055231/https://www.indiatoday.in/education-today/gk-current-affairs/story/gateway-of-india-9-facts-you-should-know-1402083-2018-12-04 | archive-date=15 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The gateway is a protected monument in Maharashtra under the aegis of the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://asi.nic.in/protected-monuments-in-maharashtra/ | title=Protected Monuments in Maharashtra | publisher=asi.nic.in | accessdate=23 September 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212105320/http://asi.nic.in/protected-monuments-in-maharashtra/ | archive-date=12 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It is a regular gathering place for locals, street vendors and photographers.{{sfn|Sarina Singh|2010|pp=783-784}}{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Morris (2005) writes, \"Today the Gateway of India has forgotten all its pompous or elegiac meanings and is a place of pleasure, habitually thronged, inside and out, by companionable crowds out for the sea air. The liners no longer come from Londond, and the only boats around the pier are pleasure crafts touting trips around the harbour, or excursions to the Elephanta Caves. It is a merry place, an ice-cream place...\".{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}}} In 2012, the [[Maharashtra Tourism Development Corporation]] moved the Elephanta Festival of Music and Dance from its original location at Elephanta Caves \u2014 where it had been celebrated for 23 years \u2014 to the gateway, due to the increased capacity offered by the venue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tembhekar|first=Chittaranjan|title=Elephanta festival 'moves' to Gateway of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-05/mumbai/31123371_1_elephanta-island-gateway-elephanta-festival|accessdate=30 April 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=5 March 2012|last2=Jaisinghani|first2=Bella|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110175139/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-05/mumbai/31123371_1_elephanta-island-gateway-elephanta-festival|archive-date=10 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The gateway can host 2,000 to 2,500 people, whereas Elephanta Caves could host only 700 to 800.<ref>{{cite news|title=Festival weaves magic|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/festival-weaves-magic/928956/|accessdate=30 November 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=27 March 2012|agency=Express News Service|location=Mumbai}}</ref>\n\nBy the year 2012, the [[Bombay Municipal Corporation]] increased the plaza area around the gateway for pedestrians by restoring the area at a cost of {{INR}}5 crores.<ref name = \"intach\">{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-not-quite-a-getaway/articleshow/12312527.cms?referral=PM | title=Gateway not quite a getaway | date=18 March 2012 | newspaper=Times of India | accessdate=16 August 2019 | author=Lewis, Clara | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110044234/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-not-quite-a-getaway/articleshow/12312527.cms?referral=PM | archive-date=10 January 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> It involved the cutting down of trees, reducing the garden area, replacing toilets and closing the car park. The redevelopment led to a dispute between the [[Indian National Trust for Art and Cultural Heritage]] (INTACH) and the Urban Design Research Institute, and the government was criticised for poor project implementation which critics alleged had failed to conform to the original plans.<ref name = \"intach\"/>\n\nIn January 2014, [[Philips|Philips Lighting India]], in association with the Maharashtra Tourism Development Corporation, undertook the expenditure of {{INR}}2 crores to illuminate the gateway, by installing an LED lighting system with sixteen million shades.<ref name=\"afaqs\">{{cite news | url=https://www.afaqs.com/news/ooh/39792_philips-shows-the-light-at-the-gateway-of-india | title=Philips shows the light at the Gateway of India | date=24 January 2019 | newspaper=Afaqs | accessdate=16 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171234/https://www.afaqs.com/news/ooh/39792_philips-shows-the-light-at-the-gateway-of-india | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Philips used products from its Philips Color Kinetics and LED street lighting, and did not receive any branding for the illumination project in which 132 light points were created, which were reportedly sixty-percent more energy efficient than the old lighting system.<ref name = \"afaqs\"/> In August 2014, the state Directorate of Archaeology and Museums had proposed conservation of the gateway by the ASI, after noting deterioration caused by [[Salinity|saline deposits]] from the sea.<ref name=\"august2014\"/> An estimate of costs was to be prepared and approved by the ASI. The last such conservation had been undertaken twenty years earlier.<ref name=\"august2014\">{{Cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/consider-chemical-conservation-of-gateway-state-tells-asi/ |title=Consider chemical conservation of Gateway, state tells ASI |last=Rao |first=Srinath Raghvendra |newspaper=The Indian Express |date=11 August 2014 |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714233824/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/consider-chemical-conservation-of-gateway-state-tells-asi/ |archive-date=14 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> An independent study had earlier been conducted at the gateway, between June 2001 and May 2002, aimed at informing future conservation of the monument understanding the degree of colour changes of stones owing to seasonal weather conditions and saturated colour of minerals.{{sfn|Tiwari, L. B.|2005|pp=788-789}} The study found the stones of the monument to appear darker during monsoon than during other seasons while the colour change in the inner portions of the monument rises with variations of seasonal humidity and temperature, given they do not face the sea, rainwater, or sunlight.{{sfn|Tiwari, L. B.|2005|pp=793-794}} It concluded with the finding that the alteration degree and overall colour change in the inner portions are higher than those in the outer portions of the monument.{{sfn|Tiwari, L. B.|2005|p=794}}\n\nIn 2015, the Maharashtra Maritime Board and the Maharashtra Coastal Zone Management Authority approved a proposal to construct a passenger jetty near Apollo Bunder and a promenade between the gateway and the [[Bombay Presidency Radio Club]].<ref name=\"Kulkarni\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-passenger-jetty-promenade-planned-at-apollo-bunder-2128420 |title=Passenger jetty, promenade planned at Apollo Bunder |last=Kulkarni |first=Dhaval |date=25 September 2015 |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis |access-date=20 September 2019 |last2=Shaikh |first2=Ateeq |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209032404/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-passenger-jetty-promenade-planned-at-apollo-bunder-2128420 |archive-date=9 December 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The project was aimed at reducing crowding at the gateway by closing all its jetties and refocusing the location solely as a tourist attraction.<ref name=\"mumbaimirror\">{{Cite news |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/with-jetty-at-apollo-bunder-gateway-to-be-clutter-free/articleshow/45860997.cms |title=With jetty at Apollo Bunder, Gateway to be clutter-free |last=Naik |first=Yogesh |date=13 January 2015 |newspaper=Mumbai Mirror |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe gateway has interested companies and corporate houses such as the [[Tata Group]], the [[RPG Group]] and the [[JSW Group]], who have expressed their wish to maintain the gateway and enhance its facilities.<ref name=\"thetribune2019\"/> This happened after the state government identified 371 heritage sites under its Maharashtra Vaibhav State Protected Monuments Adoption Scheme (MVSPMAS).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-only-2-of-371-maharashtra-s-adopt-a-monument-scheme-a-maha-flop-2612034 | title=Only 2 of 371: Maharashtra's adopt-a-monument scheme a Maha flop | date=6 May 2018 | newspaper=Daily News and Analysis | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Kulkarni, Dhaval | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814065754/https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-only-2-of-371-maharashtra-s-adopt-a-monument-scheme-a-maha-flop-2612034 | archive-date=14 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Under this scheme, companies and corporates can adopt heritage monuments and give out funds for their maintenance, to satisfy their [[corporate social responsibility]].<ref name=\"thetribune2019\"/> The scheme also provides sponsors with the opportunity to generate revenue by selling their rights to feature the heritage monuments in commercials and advertisements. Other revenue-generating opportunities include the sale of entry tickets to the site and charging for the use of facilities.<ref name=\"thetribune2019\">{{cite web | url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/gateway-of-india-other-maha-monuments-up-for-adoption-by-corporates/808216.html | title=Gateway of India, other Maha monuments up for adoption by corporates | publisher=The Tribune | date=26 July 2019 | accessdate=13 August 2019 | author=Kumar, Shiv | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813111617/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/gateway-of-india-other-maha-monuments-up-for-adoption-by-corporates/808216.html | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the Maharashtra state government initiated a plan to restore, clean, and beautify the monument. A project plan was to be prepared in a month.<ref name=\"financial\">{{cite news | url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-to-be-restored-and-beautified/1480340/ | title=Mumbai's iconic Gateway of India to be restored and beautified | date=7 February 2019 | newspaper=The Financial Express | accessdate=13 August 2019 | location=Mumbai | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813103933/https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-to-be-restored-and-beautified/1480340/ | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The state governor, [[C. Vidyasagar Rao]], directed the Bombay Municipal Corporation commissioner and architects to submit a project plan in a month on measures to be taken for the purpose.<ref name=\"asianage\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.asianage.com/metros/mumbai/080219/submit-report-on-preserving-gateway-governor.html |title=Submit report on preserving Gateway: Governor |date=8 February 2019 |newspaper=The Asian Age |access-date=13 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813110443/https://www.asianage.com/metros/mumbai/080219/submit-report-on-preserving-gateway-governor.html |archive-date=13 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"foundation1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/maharashtra-govt-plans-to-beautify-gateway-of-india/article26202879.ece |title=Maharashtra govt plans to beautify Gateway of India  |date=7 February 2019 |newspaper=The Hindu |access-date=13 August 2019}}</ref> In the same month, chemical conservation was proposed by the state archaeology department noting blackening of and algae on stones and surface cracks.  Structural stability audit had last been conducted eight years earlier with plant growth on the monument removed annually.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/plan-to-use-chemicals-to-restore-gateways-sheen/articleshow/67907833.cms | title=Plan to use chemicals to restore Gateway's sheen | date=9 February 2019 | accessdate=24 September 2019 | newspaper=The Times of India | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210150838/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/plan-to-use-chemicals-to-restore-gateways-sheen/articleshow/67907833.cms | archive-date=10 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2019 the state government agreed on a four-stage plan to manage tourists visiting the site. This involved the physical conservation of the monument, the installation of a [[Son et lumi\u00e8re (show)|sound-and-light]] show, the relocation of the anchorage around the monument and a streamlined, ticketed entry system.<ref name=\"TOIlightsound\">{{cite web | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-is-all-set-to-get-some-ground-rules/as68373878.cms | title=Mumbai's iconic Gateway of India is all set to get some ground rules | publisher=Times Travel | date=12 March 2019 | accessdate=13 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828003335/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-is-all-set-to-get-some-ground-rules/as68373878.cms | archive-date=28 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The plan followed [[UNESCO]] guidance for protected heritage sites and took into account the views of interested parties, including the Directorate of Museums and Archaeology, which has the monument within its purview; the Mumbai Port Trust, which is entrusted with the land; and the Bombay Municipal Corporation, which controls the location. The task of coming up with a suitable management plan was delegated to architects.<ref name=\"DNAReport\">{{cite web | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-mumbai-light-sound-show-low-entry-fee-to-push-gateway-tourism-2728505 | title=Mumbai: Light-&-sound show, low entry fee to push Gateway tourism | newspaper=Daily News and Analysis | date=11 March 2019 | accessdate=13 August 2019 | author=Kulkarni, Dhaval | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813113038/https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-mumbai-light-sound-show-low-entry-fee-to-push-gateway-tourism-2728505 | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, [[Snapchat]] extended its Landmarker features to the gateway by which users can superimpose [[augmented reality]] experiences on top of their pictures of the gateway.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/snapchat-landmarkers-india-monuments-gateway-of-india-taj-mahal-lens-studio-2-1-2091072 | title=Snapchat's Landmarkers Feature Enters India, Lens Studio 2.1 Released With New Templates | date=27 August 2019 | newspaper=NDTV Gadgets 360.com | accessdate=29 August 2019 | author=Singh, Jagmeet | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828112129/https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/snapchat-landmarkers-india-monuments-gateway-of-india-taj-mahal-lens-studio-2-1-2091072 | archive-date=28 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Events and incidents==\n[[File:3 December 2008 Gateway protest march 5.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Solidarity march at the gateway premises, in the aftermath of the 2008 Mumbai terror attacks]]\nThe gateway was the location of a [[25 August 2003 Mumbai bombings|terror attack on 25 August 2003]], when there was a bomb blast in front of it.<ref name=\"vanityfair\"/> The force of the explosion, from a bomb in a taxi parked near the Taj Mahal hotel, reportedly threw bystanders into the sea.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|title=2003: Bombay rocked by twin car bombs|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/25/newsid_3921000/3921475.stm|date=25 August 2003|accessdate=16 April 2012|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410202413/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/25/newsid_3921000/3921475.stm|archivedate=10 April 2012}}</ref> On 13 August 2005, a mentally unstable man stabbed two young girls from [[Manipur]] at the gateway premises.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maniac stabs girl to death at Gateway|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Maniac-stabs-girl-to-death-at-Gateway/articleshow/1200458.cms|accessdate=14 August 2005|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 August 2005|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118121653/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Maniac-stabs-girl-to-death-at-Gateway/articleshow/1200458.cms|archivedate=18 January 2018}}</ref> On New Year's Eve, 2007 a woman was groped by a mob at the gateway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gateway groping shocks Mumbai|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-groping-shocks-Mumbai/articleshow/1028075.cms|accessdate=3 January 2007|newspaper=The Times of India|date=3 January 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129014412/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-groping-shocks-Mumbai/articleshow/1028075.cms|archivedate=29 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|November 2008 Mumbai terror attacks]], which targeted the Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel opposite to the gateway, among other locations, crowds of people including news television reporters and cameramen congregated at the gateway premises.<ref name=\"vanityfair\">{{cite news | url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/11/taj-hotel-siege-200911 | title=Anatomy of a Siege | date=30 September 2009 | newspaper=Vanity Fair | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Brenner, Marie | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713232325/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/11/taj-hotel-siege-200911 | archive-date=13 July 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/asia/after-the-terrorist-attacks-the-gateway-to-india-is-open-to-the-world-8975051.html | title=After the terrorist attacks: The gateway to India is open to the world | date=30 November 2013 | newspaper=Independent | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Leadbeater, Chris | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814074444/https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/asia/after-the-terrorist-attacks-the-gateway-to-india-is-open-to-the-world-8975051.html | archive-date=14 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, public access to the area around was restricted.<ref name = \"intach\"/> Fearing further attacks on the gateway and on the Elephanta caves, the state government proposed the closure of all of the jetties at the gateway and their replacement with two new piers, to be built near the Bombay Presidency Radio Club.<ref name=dna09>{{cite news|title=5 jetties may be shut|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_5-jetties-may-be-shut_1225849|accessdate=30 April 2012|newspaper=Daily News and Analysis|date=29 January 2009}}</ref> In response to the terror attacks a solidarity march was held at the gateway premises on 3 December 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1864035,00.html |title=A Rally in Mumbai: \"Remember 26-11!\" |last=Tharoor |first=Ishaan |date=3 December 2008 |newspaper= Time |access-date=20 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202212930/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1864035,00.html |archive-date=2 December 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Show-of-solidarity-at-Gateway-of-India/articleshow/3788910.cms |title=Show of solidarity at Gateway of India |date=3 December 2008 |newspaper=Times of India |access-date=20 September 2019 |agency=PTI}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, protests were organised at the premises in the wake of the [[Pulwama attack]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pulwama-attack-mumbaikars-show-solidarity-with-crpf-martyrs-119021601097_1.html |title=Pulwama attack: Mumbaikars show solidarity with CRPF martyrs |date=16 February 2019 |newspaper=Business Standard |access-date=20 September 2019 |agency=PTI |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216212215/https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pulwama-attack-mumbaikars-show-solidarity-with-crpf-martyrs-119021601097_1.html |archive-date=16 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2020, the gateway became a site of spontaneous protests that commenced overnight, under the name of \"Occupy Gateway\", in the aftermath of the [[2020 Jawaharlal Nehru University attack|attack on Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/948950/at-occupygateway-mumbai-citizens-have-been-protesting-in-solidarity-with-jnu-for-over-16-hours | title=At #OccupyGateway, Mumbai citizens have been protesting in solidarity with JNU for over 16 hours | work=Scroll | date=6 January 2020 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Johari, Aarefa | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218121250/https://scroll.in/article/948950/at-occupygateway-mumbai-citizens-have-been-protesting-in-solidarity-with-jnu-for-over-16-hours | archive-date=18 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Protestors were later relocated from the gateway premises to [[Azad Maidan]] in Mumbai to ease the movement of traffic and people.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/mumbai-protest-protesters-evicted-from-gateway-of-india-and-relocated-to-azad-maidan/article30501355.ece | title=Mumbai protest: Protesters evicted from Gateway of India and relocated to Azad Maidan | work=Hindustan Times | date=7 January 2020 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Sheth, Himani | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108165821/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/mumbai-protest-protesters-evicted-from-gateway-of-india-and-relocated-to-azad-maidan/article30501355.ece | archive-date=8 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/jnu-violence-protestors-relocated-from-gateway-of-india-to-azad-maidan-to-avoid-inconvenience-to-citizens-claims-mumbai-police-7870561.html | title=JNU violence: Protestors 'relocated' from Gateway of India to Azad Maidan to avoid inconvenience to citizens, claims Mumbai Police | work=Firstpost | date=7 January 2020 | agency=Press Trust of India | accessdate=18 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108214751/https://www.firstpost.com/india/jnu-violence-protestors-relocated-from-gateway-of-india-to-azad-maidan-to-avoid-inconvenience-to-citizens-claims-mumbai-police-7870561.html | archive-date=8 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:The Apollo Bunder- the Gate of India.jpg|Apollo Bunder, in 1905, with the location where the gateway stands today\nFile:Gateway of india a.jpg|Pigeons on the gateway grounds\nFile:Gateway of India aerial view.jpg|Aerial view of the gateway, with its erstwhile gardened esplanade\nFile:India Mumbai Victor Grigas 2011-7.jpg|''[[Jali]]'' work on the arches\nFile:Gateway of India - 11 (Friar's Balsam Flickr).jpg|Floral motifs, as seen on the gateway\nFile:Gateway of India - turret.jpg|Close-up of a turret\nFile:Gateway of india's look in evening.jpg|The gateway, lit up in the evening\nFile:Arch of Gateway of India.jpg|Internal view of the dome, with ''[[muqarnas]]'' designs\nFile:Beating Retreat and Tattoo ceremony at Gateway of India, 2018 (9).jpg|Beating the Retreat and Tattoo Ceremony at the gateway, on [[Navy Day (India)|Navy Day]] in 2018\nFile:Gateway of India , Hotel Taj and ,Oberoi Hotels , Mumbai, Mahrashtra, India.jpg|The gateway, as seen with the Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel\nFile:A photographer advertising his sevices at the Gateway of India (18566738741).jpg|Photographer offering services, in the vicinity of the gateway\nFile:Indian farmers at Gateway of India.png|Farmers engaged in an awareness campaign at the gateway\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua|30em}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes and news reports===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Books and journals===\n{{Refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book|ref = {{harvid|Civic Affairs|1961}}|title=Civic Affairs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aOkmAQAAIAAJ|year=1961|publisher=P. C. Kapoor at the Citizen Press}}\n* {{cite book|ref = {{harvid|Bombay Civic Journal|1975}}|title=The Bombay Civic Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N4zRyapZSRMC|year=1975|publisher=Municipal Corporation of Greater Bombay}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=A. K. Bag|title=History of Technology in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lDshAQAAIAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Indian National Science Academy}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Ajoy Kumar Sen|title=Tourism in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ugbAAAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Modern Book Agency}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Anthony Hewitt|title=Corridors of Time: Distant Footsteps Through the Empire 1914-1948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GHduAAAAMAAJ|year=1993|publisher=Pentland|isbn=978-1-85821-092-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=B.K. Chaturvedi|title=Tourist Centers Of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QrLcFkhRZPYC|year=2002|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd.|isbn=978-81-7182-137-2}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=B. Karunakar|title=Corporate Champions: Excellent Companies of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aqKoDwAAQBAJ|date=7 December 2011|publisher=SAGE Publishing India|isbn=978-81-321-1919-7}}\n* {{cite journal | ref=harv|title=Religion and identity in India's heritage tourism | author=Bandyopadhyay, Ranjan | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | year=2008 | volume=35 | issue=3 | pages=790\u2013808 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2008.06.004 |display-authors=et al.}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Berlitz|title=Berlitz Pocket Guide India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0StHDwAAQBAJ|date=1 August 2017|publisher=Apa Publications|isbn=978-1-78573-058-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Bombay State Road Transport Corporation|title=State Transport Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xRbWAAAAMAAJ|volume=9|year=1958}}\n* {{Britannica|72526|Mumbai - Cultural Life|Chakravarthi Raghavan}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Charles Edward Trevelyan|title=On the Education of the People of India|url=https://archive.org/details/oneducationpeop00trevgoog|year=1838|publisher=Longman, Orme, Brown, Green & Longmans|author-link=Sir Charles Trevelyan, 1st Baronet}}\n* {{cite journal | ref=harv | title=Gateway to the globe | author=Chatterji, Monojit | journal=The World Today | year=1997 | volume=53 | issue=8/9 | pages=233\u2013234 |jstor=40475975}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=DK Travel|title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K51tBAAAQBAJ|date=1 October 2014|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Limited|isbn=978-0-241-01348-9}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=de Bruyn, Pipa|display-authors=et al.|title=Frommer's India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X1ksAQAAMAAJ|date=4 March 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470556108}}\n* {{cite book | ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/?id=poQPvwEACAAJ&dq=frommers+india+2008 | title=Frommer's India | publisher=Wiley | author=de Bruyn, Pipa|display-authors=et al. | year=2010 | isbn=9780470556108}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Deepa Gahlot|title=Take-2: 50 Films That Deserve a New Audience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JEqwDAAAQBAJ|date=1 October 2015|publisher=Hay House, Inc|isbn=978-93-84544-85-0|author-link=Deepa Gahlot}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv| url=https://books.google.com/?id=UpT2CwAAQBAJ&dq=queen+mary+king+george+cardboard+structure | title=Traveling India in the Age of Gandhi | publisher=University Press of America | author=Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N. | year=2008 | isbn = 9781461693116}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Gillian Tindall|title=City of Gold: The Biography of Bombay|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fKwmBWs-jGMC|year=1992|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-009500-5|author-link=Gillian Tindall}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Helio San Miguel|title=World Film Locations: Mumbai|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lsCrDwAAQBAJ|date=21 September 2012|publisher=Intellect Books|isbn=978-1-84150-679-1}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author1=Jagir Singh Bajwa|author2=Ravinder Kaur|title=Tourism Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TVXCiwdwPxsC|year=2007|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-313-0047-3}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Jan Morris|title=Stones of Empire: The Buildings of the Raj|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8zD1Ugfq9KwC|year=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-280596-6|author-link=Jan Morris}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Kirpal Sigh Annie Mathew|title=Middle School Social Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RyohfLCDOUkC|publisher=Frank Brothers|isbn=978-81-8409-103-8}}\n* {{cite journal | ref=harv|title='The Viceroys are Disappearing from the Roundabouts in Delhi': British symbols of power in post-colonial India | author=McGarr, Paul M. | journal=Modern Asian Studies | year=2015 | volume=49 | issue=3 | pages=787\u2013831 | doi=10.1017/s0026749x14000080| doi-access=free }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Melody S. Mis|title=How to Draw India's Sights and Symbols|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JsWERNisCTgC|date=15 December 2004|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|isbn=978-1-4042-2732-3}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Narasingha Prosad Sil|title=Swami Vivekananda: A Reassessment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pTDPlJPyV_MC|year=1997|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|isbn=978-0-945636-97-7|author-link=Narasingha Sil}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author= P. K. Agrawal|title=Indian Culture, Art and Heritage|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1cJmDwAAQBAJ|publisher=Prabhat Prakashan|isbn=978-93-5266-926-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Renu Saran|title=Monuments of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xHNOBAAAQBAJ|date=19 August 2014|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books Pvt Ltd|isbn=978-93-5165-298-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Sarina Singh|title=Lonely Planet India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vK88ktao7pIC&pg=PA783|date=15 September 2010|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications|isbn=978-1-74220-347-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author1=Sharada Dwivedi|author2=Rahul Mehrotra|title=Bombay: The Cities Within|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RuhOAAAAMAAJ|year=1995|publisher=India Book House|isbn=978-81-85028-80-4|author1-link=Sharada Dwivedi}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author1=Sharada Dwivedi|author2=Rahul Mehrotra|title=Fort walks: around Bombay's Fort area|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rTRuAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Eminence Designs|isbn=978-81-900602-3-3}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first1=Sherry|last1= Simon|first2=Paul |last2=St-Pierre|title=Changing the Terms: Translating in the Postcolonial Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cmJ5O0ZOwqsC|year=2000|publisher=University of Ottawa Press|isbn=978-0-7766-0524-1}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Shobhna Gupta|title=Monuments of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W4r5iLMVGkAC|year=2003|publisher=Har-Anand Publications|isbn=978-81-241-0926-7}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Robert W. Bradnock|title=South Asian Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=le8uAQAAIAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Trade & Travel Publications}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Tejaswini Niranjana|title=Siting Translation: History, Post-Structuralism, and the Colonial Context|url=https://archive.org/details/sitingtranslatio0000nira|url-access=registration|date=8 January 1992|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-91136-9}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Timothy H. Parsons|title=The Second British Empire: In the Crucible of the Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urpKBAAAQBAJ|date=7 August 2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4422-3529-8}}\n* {{cite journal | ref=harv|title=Weathering impact on the colour of building stones of the 'Gateway of India' monument | author=Tiwari, L. B. |display-authors=et al.| journal=Environmental Geology | year=2005 | volume=48 | issue=6 | pages=788\u2013794 | doi=10.1007/s00254-005-0020-4|bibcode=2005EnGeo..48..788T }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/place/Gateway+Of+India+Mumbai/@18.9222281,72.8346631,2a,75y,222.56h,90.21t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1snjNnaONbfz98G8zuMYztCg!2e0!7i13312!8i6656!4m12!1m6!3m5!1s0x3be7d1c73a0d5cad:0xc70a25a7209c733c!2sGateway+Of+India+Mumbai!8m2!3d18.9219841!4d72.8346543!3m4!1s0x3be7d1c73a0d5cad:0xc70a25a7209c733c!8m2!3d18.9219841!4d72.8346543 Interactive 360\u00b0 imagery of the gateway]\n* {{osmrelation-inline|6356858}}\n\n{{Mumbai topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Tourist attractions in Mumbai|state=collapsed}}\n{{Portalbar|India|Architecture|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Stone buildings]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1924]]\n[[Category:Indo-Saracenic Revival architecture]]\n[[Category:Gates in India]]\n[[Category:Triumphal arches in India]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Mary of Teck]]\n[[Category:George V]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Short description|Arch-monument in Mumbai, India}}\n{{Distinguish|text = the [[India Gate]],  the World War I war memorial in New Delhi}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox building\n| building_name       = Gateway of India\n| native_building_name= \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     =\n| image               = Mumbai 03-2016 30 Gateway of India.jpg\n| caption             = \n| map_type            = India Mumbai#India Maharashtra#India \n| building_type       = [[Triumphal arch]]\n| architectural_style = [[Indo-Saracenic]]\n| structural_system   =\n| cost                = {{INR}}21 lakhs\n| ren_cost            =\n| location            = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| address             =\n| owner               = [[Archaeological Survey of India]]\n|coordinates     = {{coord|18.9219|72.8346|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption     = Location of Gateway of India in Maharashtra\n| start_date          = 31 March 1913\n| completion_date     = 1924\n| inauguration_date   = 4 December 1924\n| renovation_date     =\n| height              = {{convert|26|m|ft|abbr=on|0}}\n| diameter            = {{convert|15|m|ft|0|abbr=off}}\n| other_dimensions    =\n| floor_area          =\n| main_contractor     =\n| architect           = [[George Wittet]]\n| architecture_firm   = [[Gammon India]]\n| structural_engineer =\n| services_engineer   =\n| civil_engineer      =\n| other_designers     =\n| quantity_surveyor   =\n| awards              =\n| ren_architect       = George Wittet\n| website             = [https://gatewayofindia.org gatewayofindia.org]\n| ren_firm            =\n| ren_str_engineer    =\n| ren_serv_engineer   =\n| ren_civ_engineer    =\n| ren_oth_designers   =\n| ren_qty_surveyor    =\n| ren_awards          =\n| references          =\n}}\n\nThe '''Gateway of India''' is an arch-monument built in the early twentieth century in the city of [[Mumbai]], in the [[India]]n state of [[Maharashtra]]. It was erected to commemorate the landing in December 1911 at [[Apollo Bunder]], Mumbai (then Bombay) of [[Emperor of India|King-Emperor]] [[George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen-Empress Mary]], the first British monarch to visit India. At the time of the royal visit, the gateway was not yet built, and a cardboard structure greeted the monarch. The foundation stone was laid in March 1913 for a monument built in the [[Indo-Saracenic]] style, incorporating elements of 16th-century Marathi architecture. The final design of the monument by architect [[George Wittet]] was sanctioned only in 1914, and construction was completed in 1924. The structure is a [[triumphal arch]] made of [[basalt]], which is {{convert|26|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} high.\n\nAfter its construction the gateway was used as a symbolic ceremonial entrance to British India for important colonial personnel. It has been called a symbol of \"conquest and colonisation\" commemorating British colonial legacy. The gateway is also the monument from where the last British troops left India in 1948, following Indian independence. It is located on the waterfront at an angle, opposite the [[The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel|Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel]] and overlooks the [[Arabian Sea]]. Today, the monument is synonymous with the city of Mumbai, and is amongst its prime tourist attractions. The gateway is also a gathering spot for locals, street vendors, and photographers soliciting services. It holds significance for the local Jewish community as it has been the spot for [[Hanukkah]] celebrations, with the lighting of the [[Menorah (Hanukkah)|menorah]], since 2003. There are five jetties located at the gateway, of which two are used for commercial ferry operations.\n\nThe gateway was the site of a [[25 August 2003 Mumbai bombings|terror attack in August 2003]], when there was a bomb blast in a taxi parked in front of it. Access to the gateway was restricted after people congregated at its premises following the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|2008 Mumbai terror attacks]], in which the Taj Hotel opposite the gateway and other locations in its vicinity were targeted.\n\nIn March 2019, the Maharashtra state government proposed a four-step plan to develop the location for the convenience of tourists, following a direction issued by the state governor in February 2019.\n\n==History and significance==\n{{multiple image|perrow=1/1|total_width=200|| align=left|caption_align=left\n| image1 = Gateway of India, Bombay. 1911.JPG|caption1=The gateway, in 1924\n| image2 = Departure of British Troops from India - 28 February 1948 - Gateway of India.jpg|caption2=Departure of the last British troops from the gateway, in 1948}}\nThe gateway was built to commemorate the arrival of George V, Emperor of India and Mary of Teck, Empress consort, in India at Apollo Bunder, Mumbai (then Bombay) on 2 December 1911 prior to the [[Delhi Durbar|Delhi Durbar of 1911]]; it was the first visit of a British monarch to India.{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}}{{sfn|Anthony Hewitt|1993|p=173}}{{sfn|Timothy H. Parsons|2014|p=3}} However, they only got to see a cardboard model of the monument,{{efn-ua|group=note|While Dup\u00e9e (2008) notes that the king and queen passed through a \"temporarily constructed mock cardboard and [[pastiche]] structure\",{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}} de Bruyn et al. (2008) note the same simply as a \"fake cardboard structure\"{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2008|p=92}}.}} as construction did not begin until 1915.{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}}{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=92}} The foundation stone for the gateway was laid on 31 March 1913 by then governor of Bombay, [[Sir George Sydenham Clarke]] with the final design of [[George Wittet]] for the gateway sanctioned in August 1914.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra1999|p=42}}{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=92}} Before the gateway's construction, Apollo Bunder used to serve a native fishing ground.{{sfn|Gillian Tindall|1992|p=6-7}} Between 1915 and 1919 work continued at the Apollo Bunder to reclaim the land on which the gateway was to be built, along with the construction of a sea wall.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra1999|p=42}} [[Gammon India]] had undertaken construction work for the gateway.{{sfn|Renu Saran|2014|loc = ch. on 'Gateway of India}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Gammon India claims to have done India's first pre-cast reinforced concrete piling for the foundations of the gateway.{{sfn|B. Karunakar|2011|loc= ch. on 'Gammon India Ltd.'}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gammonindia.com/projects/landmark-project-for-gammon-india.htm |title=Landmark Projects |website=www.gammonindia.com |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219044719/http://www.gammonindia.com/projects/landmark-project-for-gammon-india.htm |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} Its foundations were completed in 1920 while construction was finished in 1924.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1995|p=118}}{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra1999|p=42}} The gateway was opened to the public on 4 December 1924 by then viceroy, [[Rufus Isaacs, 1st Marquess of Reading]].{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1995}} Following Indian independence, the last British troops to leave India, the First Battalion of the [[Somerset Light Infantry]], passed through the gateway with a 21-gun salute, as part of a ceremony on 28 February 1948, signalling the end of the [[British Raj]].{{sfn|Robert W. Bradnock|1994}}{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Morris (2005) writes about the gateway, \"This was where the British landed: and this where, in the end, they left. The Gateway of India did not see many ceremonial arrivals after all, during its three decades under British rule, but it formed the background to one historical departure \u2014 the last parade with which, in 1947, the British said goodbye to their Indian Empire.\"{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}}}\n\nN. Kamala, professor at [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jnu.ac.in/content/nkamala |title=N. Kamala |website=jnu.ac.in |publisher=Jawaharlal Nehru University |access-date=19 September 2019}}</ref> refers to the gateway as a \"jewel in the crown\" and a \"symbol of conquest and colonisation\".{{sfn|SimonSt-Pierre|2000|p=245|loc=chpt. 13}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Kamala (2000) writes, \"Through the Gateway, the imperial traveller could perceive in his mind's eye the vision of a subject-nation, a nation constructed and processed in and for his gaze. As Tejaswini Niranjana points out, one of the professed aims of English education was to give the colonized, \"along with the English language, models of national culture\" (1992, 107),{{sfn|Tejaswini Niranjana|1992|p=107}} the stated objectives being to \"give a liberal English education to the middle and upper classes, in order that we may furnish them with both the materials and models for the formation of a national literature\" (Trevelyan 1838, 175).{{sfn|Charles Edward Trevelyan|1838|p=175}} While various notions of India\u2014indeed, various Indias\u2014may have pre-existed British colonization, this one monolithic nation, India, was constructed only in English translation. The Gateway of India looked outward, welcoming the colonizer, a symbol and facilitator of appropriation, but it also looked inward, bringing a people together (and driving them apart) as they dutifully defined their nation in the curiously perceived neutrality of the English language.\"{{sfn|SimonSt-Pierre|2000|p=245|loc=chpt. 13}}}} The monument commemorates the legacy of British colonial rule, namely the first visit of a British monarch to India and its use as an entry point for prominent colonial personnel into British India.{{sfn|SimonSt-Pierre|2000|p=245}} Today the gateway is synonymous with the city of Mumbai.<ref name = \"deccan\" /><ref name=\"Kulkarni\"/>{{efn-ua|group=note|The gateway has also been featured in films shot in or with stories based in Mumbai. Ranjani Mazumdar (2010), referring to the 1989 Indian film ''[[Parinda]]'', writes, \"In a city where the rich and poor live cheek by jowl, where disenchantment is the experience of the majority, Mumbai Noir has become synonymous with urban decay, crime, claustrophobia, and an assortment of characters marked by some sort of death wish...Karan is soon sucked into a vortex of violence in a narrative that consciously uses Mumbai's familiar locations like the Gateway of India, the Babulnath Temple, the fountains and various abandoned factories...Urban space is not just the backdrop but a central character in the film and the use of the Gateway of India to stage a bloody climax paved the way for a new imagination of violence.\"{{sfn|Helio San Miguel|2012|loc= chpt. on 'Mumbai Noir'}}<br/>There is also a 1957 Indian film titled ''Gateway of India'' featuring the monument, starring [[Madhubala]] and [[Om Prakash]].{{sfn|Deepa Gahlot2015|loc=chpt. on 'Gateway of India (1957)'}}}} Since its construction, the gateway has remained amongst the first structures visible to visitors arriving in Bombay by the sea.{{sfn|Chatterji, Monojit|1997|pp=233-234}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Tindall (1992) writes, \"If Bombay is, as some think, an Indian city with a Western fa\u00e7ade, then the Gateway and the Taj{{efn-ua|group=note|Referring to the [[The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel|Taj Mahal Palace Hotel]] located opposite the gateway, both visible together from the sea.}} are this fa\u00e7ade in spite of their determinedly oriental opulence.\"{{sfn|Gillian Tindall|1992|p=12}} While Dup\u00e9e (2008) writes, \"The city's dramatical imperial arch graced the harbor's approach, lending substance to the characterization that Bombay was the \"gateway\" or \"front door\" to the subcontinent, not unlike, according to one author, the [[Arc de Triomphe]]'s as entryway into the city of [[Paris]]...The arch of honey-colored basalt was not completed until 1924, but once erected it became for travellers the city's dominant architectural icon. The Taj Mahal Hotel, situated nearby, also faced the harbour, commanding a stunning view of the sea and, dependent upon the traveller's aesthetic tastes, lending an imposing grandeur to the city's image.\"{{sfn|Dup\u00e9e, Jeffrey N.|2008|p=114}} Yet Monojit (1997) notes, \"Visible from way out at sea, it was the first sight of normality in what was to be an alien land...Today, the Gateway is a favourite promenade spot for thousands of Bomabyites...the Gateway that once symbolised Imperial rule still symbolises the city's closeness to the West, its contact with the outside world.\"{{sfn|Chatterji, Monojit|1997|p=233}}}}\n\nSince 2003, the gateway has been the location for the local Jewish community to light the menorah for Hanukkah celebrations every year.<ref name=\"hanukkah\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://religionnews.com/2018/12/14/photos-of-the-week-52/ | title=Photos of the Week | date=14 December 2018 | newspaper=Religion News Service | accessdate=16 August 2019 | author=Doyle, Kit | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171233/https://religionnews.com/2018/12/14/photos-of-the-week-52/ | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> This ritual was started by [[Gavriel Holtzberg|Rabbi Gavriel Noach Holtzberg]] of the chabad in Mumbai (located in [[Nariman House]]).<ref name=\"hanukkah\">{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/hanukkah-lights-up-at-gateway-of-india-with-a-wish-to-spread-light-and-love/ | title=Hanukkah lights up at Gateway of India, with a wish to spread light and love | newspaper=Indian Express | date=21 December 2014 | accessdate=16 August 2019 | author=Iyer, Kavitha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171256/https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/hanukkah-lights-up-at-gateway-of-india-with-a-wish-to-spread-light-and-love/ | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It also became a site for prayers following the 2008 Mumbai terror attacks which targeted, amongst others, Nariman House.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/baby-moshe-s-grandparents-in-mumbai-to-conduct-prayers/story-6EZOIHtEqO8s5KpQ3Zpb1K.html | title=Baby Moshe's grandparents in Mumbai, to conduct prayers | date=25 December 2008 | newspaper=Hindustan Times | accessdate=16 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171231/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/baby-moshe-s-grandparents-in-mumbai-to-conduct-prayers/story-6EZOIHtEqO8s5KpQ3Zpb1K.html | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Rabbi Holtzberg lost his life in the 2008 terror attacks.<ref name = \"hanukkah\"/>\n\n==Design and architecture==\n[[File:Gateway of India inscriptions.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Inscription on the gateway reading: \"Erected to commemorate the landing in India of their Imperial Majesties King George V and Queen Mary on the Second of December MCMXI\"]]\nThe gateway's arch has a height of {{convert|26|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} with its central dome being {{convert|15|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} in diameter.{{sfn|P. K. Agrawal|loc=chpt. on ' Gateway of India}}{{sfn|Renu Saran|2014|loc=ch. on 'Gateway of India}} The monument is built of yellow basalt and reinforced concrete.{{sfn|Melody S. Mis|2004|p=42}} The stones were sourced locally while the perforated screens were brought in from [[Gwalior]].{{sfn|Jagir Singh BajwaRavinder Kaur|2007|p=240}} The monument faces towards the Mumbai Harbour.{{sfn|Sarina Singh|2010|pp=783-784}} There are four turrets on the structure of the gateway, and there are steps constructed behind the arch of the gateway which lead to the Arabian Sea.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{Britannica|72526|Mumbai - Cultural Life|Chakravarthi Raghavan}}</ref> The monument features intricate stone [[latticework]] (also known as the ''[[jali]]'' work).{{sfn|P. K. Agrawal|loc=chpt. on ' Gateway of India}} The Scottish architect, [[George Wittet]] combined elements of the [[Roman triumphal arch]] and 16th-century architecture of Gujarat.{{sfn|Shobhna Gupta2003|p=111}}{{efn-ua|group=note| Bandyopadhyay et al. (2008) write, \"The Indian government's efforts in this portrayal of the Hindu heritage is nowhere more prominent than the mention of the Gateway of India architecture in Mumbai...it was stressed that though the British rulers designed the Gateway, it was according to the Gujarat (one of the Indian states) style.\"{{sfn|Bandyopadhyay, Ranjan|2008|p=801}}}} The architecture also combines indigenous architectural elements with elements of Islamic architecture, known as the Indo-Saracenic.{{sfn|Kirpal Sigh Annie Mathew|p=8}} The harbour front was realigned in order to make an esplanade, which would sweep down to the centre of the town. On each side of the arch, there are large halls with the capacity to hold 600 people.{{sfn|Melody S. Mis|2004|p=42}} The cost of the construction was {{INR}}21 lakhs (two million one hundred thousand rupees), borne by the then government.{{sfn|Renu Saran|2014|loc=ch. on 'Gateway of India}} Due to a paucity of funds, the approach road was never built. Hence, the gateway stands at an angle to the road leading up to it.{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1995}}\n\nIn February 2019, Seagate Technology and CyArk embarked on a mission to digitally record and preserve the gateway, by digital scanning and archiving of the monument.<ref name = \"deccan\"/> The images and data collected will be used to make photo-real three dimensional models.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/putting-the-gateway-on-the-cloud/article26334296.ece | title=Digitally recreating the Gateway of India | date=22 February 2019 | newspaper=The Hindu | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Karangutkar, Suyash}}</ref> This is a part of CyArk's international programme for digitally preserving heritage monuments.<ref name=\"deccan\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/gateway-india-be-digitally-719577.html | title=Gateway of India to be digitally preserved | date=21 February 2019 | newspaper=Deccan Herald | accessdate=13 August 2019 | author=Bose, Mrityunjay | location=Mumbai | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813105317/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/gateway-india-be-digitally-719577.html | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It involves aerial surveys conducted with terrestrial laser scanning (LiDAR), drones and [[photogrammetry]] exercises.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://cio.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/corporate-news/seagate-partners-with-cyark-to-digitally-preserve-the-gateway-of-india/68095055 | title=Seagate partners with CyArk to digitally preserve the Gateway of India | date=21 February 2019 | newspaper=Economic TImes | accessdate=14 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814071353/https://cio.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/corporate-news/seagate-partners-with-cyark-to-digitally-preserve-the-gateway-of-india/68095055 | archive-date=14 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The drawings and three-dimensional models will inform any future reconstruction works.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/pvt-firms-scan-every-square-cm-of-gateway-of-india-to-digitally-preserve-the-monument/articleshow/68100647.cms | title=Pvt firms scan every square cm of Gateway of India to 'digitally preserve' the monument | date=21 February 2019 | newspaper=The Times of India | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Jaisinghani, Bella | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731043311/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/pvt-firms-scan-every-square-cm-of-gateway-of-india-to-digitally-preserve-the-monument/articleshow/68100647.cms | archive-date=31 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Location and jetties==\n[[File:Emperor of Maratha India.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Statue of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj, in the vicinity of the gateway]]\nThe gateway stands at an angle, opposite to the Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel, which was built in 1903.{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=125}} In the grounds of the gateway, opposite the monument, stands the statue of [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj]], the [[Maratha]] warrior-hero who fought against the [[Mughal empire]] to establish the [[Maratha empire]] in the 17th century.{{sfn|Berlitz|2017}}{{sfn|B.K. Chaturvedi|2002|p=146}} The statue was unveiled on 26 January 1961 on the occasion of India's [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]].{{sfn|Bombay Civic Journal|1975|p=59}}{{sfn|Civic Affairs|1961|p=91}} It replaced a bronze statue of King-Emperor George V which stood at its place.{{sfn|Bombay Civic Journal|1975|p=39}}{{sfn|Civic Affairs|1961|p=86}}{{efn-ua|group=note|McGarr (2015) writes, \"In July 1959, in Bombay, moves were set in train to replace a statue of George V, which stood next to the Gateway of India on the city\u2019s waterfront, with a \ufb01gure of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj, a renowned Maratha warrior. As one of the best-known royal statues in India, the decision elicited strong feelings among those on both sides of the statues debate. One British expatriate living in Bombay, wrote to the editor of ''[[The Times of India]]'' to decry \u2018the limits [to] which petty-mindedness and nationalistic feeling can be carried\u2019. Back in London, [[William Haley]], editor of ''[[The Times]]'', echoed such sentiment...Haley wrote to a friend, \u2018this business of removing statues is really rather nonsense. Rather like un-writing history in [[George Orwell]]\u2019s ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four|1984]]''. What is done is done and there is no reason for the Indians to be ashamed of it...When will man-kind grow up?\u2019 Of\ufb01cial Indian sentiment, however, had begun to turn decisively against the retention of British statues in public locations. In September 1961, in Maharashtra (a new state carved from the former [[Bombay presidency]] along linguistic lines) a committee established to look into the retention of British monuments reported that none of the state\u2019s British statues could be regarded as offensive to Indian nationalism, and extremely few had been defaced. Nonetheless, the committee recommended the progressive replacement of British iconography with that \u2018more in consonance with the sense of patriotism and nationalism which has developed since the attainment of Independence in 1947\u2019...In [[Calcutta]], municipal authorities announced that statues of Lord Lawrence and [[Queen Victoria]], which stood in prominent positions in the heart of the city, would be replaced by \ufb01gures of the Indian nationalist icons...Only in [[New Delhi]], it seemed, was a nationwide trend towards the removal of British statuary. The continued presence of British iconography in India\u2019s capital was shortly, however, to become a matter of contentious political debate.\"{{sfn|McGarr, Paul M.|2015|p=814}}}} In 2016, ''[[Mid Day]]'' reported that the George V statue is kept locked in a tin shed belonging to the [[Central_Public_Works_Department#State_Public_Works_Departments_in_India|Public Works Department]], behind [[Elphinstone College]], in [[Fort (Mumbai precinct)|Fort]], Mumbai.<ref name=\"georgepancham\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/mumbai-sculptors-kin-seek-to-save-king-george-v-from-shabby-pwd-shed/17111153 |title=Mumbai: Sculptor's kin seek to save King George V from shabby PWD shed |last=Puranik |first=Apoorva |date=7 April 2016 |work=Mid Day |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170726130633/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/mumbai-sculptors-kin-seek-to-save-king-george-v-from-shabby-pwd-shed/17111153 |archive-date=26 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The George V statue was sculpted by G. K. Mhatre,{{sfn|A. K. Bag|2001|p=83}}{{sfn|Bombay State Road Transport Corporation|1958|p=36}} who has over 300 sculptures to his credit in India.<ref name=\"georgepancham\"/> Hemant Pathare, Mhatre's great-grandson and Sandeep Dahisarkar, a historian, researcher, and academician, have made efforts to relocate the George V statue to a museum, the latter of whom has reasserted the statue as ''[[Swadeshi_movement#Etymology|swadeshi]]'' art.<ref name=\"georgepancham\"/> The other statue in the locality of the gateway is that of [[Swami Vivekananda]],{{sfn|Ajoy Kumar Sen1991|p=320}}{{sfn|Sharada DwivediRahul Mehrotra|1999|p=47}} an Indian monk who is credited as a key figure in the introduction of Indian philosophies such as [[Vedanta]] and [[Yoga]] to the west, and with bringing [[Hinduism]] to the status of a major world religion during the late 19th century.{{sfn|Narasingha Prosad Sil|1997}}{{efn-ua|group=note| Bandyopadhyay et al. (2008), referring to the renaming of colonial names of cities and locations, write, \"...although the Gateway is associated with colonial heritage, which the Indian government also embraces, it wants to make a point that the Hindus were not short of renowned leaders/personalities (here in the case of two statues, Swami Vivekananda who is arguably India's greatest spiritual celebrity, and Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj who was arguably one of the country's most respected Hindu rulers). This resistance, it can be argued is targeted in opposition to the Western colonial influence which...is a \"psychological state resulting from suppressed feelings of envy and hatred.\"{{sfn|Bandyopadhyay, Ranjan|2008|p=801}}<br/>In 2017, [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] member [[Raj K. Purohit]], who has held six terms in the [[Maharashtra Legislative Assembly]], demanded the gateway to be renamed \"Bharat Dwaar\" (the [[Hindi language|Hindi]] translation of \"the gateway of India\") to ensure an \"Indian name\" for the monument and to let go of India's \"colonial hangover\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/bjp-mla-in-mumbai-wants-gateway-of-india-renamed-to-bharatdwar/story-33HkO0fsmxDjx4i996WOuL.html |title=BJP MLA in Mumbai wants Gateway of India renamed to 'Bharatdwar' |last=Rawal |first=Swapnil |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=11 June 2017 |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113012322/https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/bjp-mla-in-mumbai-wants-gateway-of-india-renamed-to-bharatdwar/story-33HkO0fsmxDjx4i996WOuL.html |archive-date=13 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He further claimed the monument to be a \"symbol of slavery\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/617331/rename-gateway-india-bharat-dwaar.html | title=Rename Gateway of India as Bharat Dwaar: BJP MLA | date=14 June 2017 | accessdate=23 September 2019 | newspaper=Deccan Herald | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620035939/https://www.deccanherald.com/content/617331/rename-gateway-india-bharat-dwaar.html | archive-date=20 June 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\nThere are five jetties located around the monument.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/mumbaiterrorstrike/Story.aspx?ID=NEWEN20090081499&type=News |title=Gateway of India jetties to move location |last=Thakkar |first=Dharmesh |date=27 January 2009 |newspaper=NDTV |access-date=30 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212011149/http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/mumbaiterrorstrike/Story.aspx?ID=NEWEN20090081499&type=News |archive-date=12 February 2011}}</ref> The first jetty is exclusive to the [[Bhabha Atomic Research Centre]], while the second and third are used for commercial ferry operations, the fourth one is closed, and the fifth is exclusive to the [[Royal Bombay Yacht Club]].{{sfn|DK Travel|2014|p=450}} The second and third jetties are the starting point for tourists to reach the [[Elephanta Caves]], which are fifty minutes away by boat from the monument.{{sfn|de Bruyn, Pipa|2010|p=125}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-heritage-week-revisiting-a-lost-culture-in-the-city-of-caves_1677368 |title=Mumbai heritage week: Revisiting a lost culture in the city of caves |date=18 April 2012 |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis |access-date=18 April 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627181825/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-heritage-week-revisiting-a-lost-culture-in-the-city-of-caves_1677368 |archive-date=27 June 2012}}</ref> Other routes from the gateway include ferry rides to [[Rewas]], [[Mandwa, Maharashtra|Mandwa]] and [[Alibaug]], while cruises also operate from the gateway.<ref name=dna09/> These ferries reportedly carry an overload of daily passengers.<ref name=\"md11\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mid-day.com/news/2011/oct/021011-Disaster-floats-at-gateway.htm |title=Disaster floats at gateway |date=2 October 2011 |newspaper=Mid Day |access-date=30 April 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308164442/http://www.mid-day.com/news/2011/oct/021011-Disaster-floats-at-gateway.htm |archive-date=8 March 2012}}</ref> The [[Mumbai Port Trust]] licenses vessels to use the gateway while the [[Maharashtra Maritime Board]] issues fitness certificates to them.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/jetty-off-nariman-point-to-give-easier-access-to-proposed-mid-sea-shivaji-memorial/story-aA7xOtuHZFmzrWwg9XY9jO.html |title=Jetty off Nariman Point to give easier access to proposed mid-sea Shivaji Memorial |last=Rawal |first=Swapnil |date=1 November 2018 |newspaper=Hindustan Times |access-date=20 September 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190917194350/https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/jetty-off-nariman-point-to-give-easier-access-to-proposed-mid-sea-shivaji-memorial/story-aA7xOtuHZFmzrWwg9XY9jO.html |archive-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism and development==\n[[File:WNC personnel cleaning the premises of the Gateway of India on World Environment Day 2015.JPG|thumb|right|200px|[[Western Naval Command]] personnel participating in a cleaning drive at the gateway, on occasion of World Environment Day in 2015]]\nThe gateway is amongst the prime tourist attractions in Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/education-today/gk-current-affairs/story/gateway-of-india-9-facts-you-should-know-1402083-2018-12-04 | title=Gateway of India: 9 facts you should know | publisher=India Today | date=4 December 2018 | accessdate=15 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815055231/https://www.indiatoday.in/education-today/gk-current-affairs/story/gateway-of-india-9-facts-you-should-know-1402083-2018-12-04 | archive-date=15 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The gateway is a protected monument in Maharashtra under the aegis of the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://asi.nic.in/protected-monuments-in-maharashtra/ | title=Protected Monuments in Maharashtra | publisher=asi.nic.in | accessdate=23 September 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212105320/http://asi.nic.in/protected-monuments-in-maharashtra/ | archive-date=12 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It is a regular gathering place for locals, street vendors and photographers.{{sfn|Sarina Singh|2010|pp=783-784}}{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}{{efn-ua|group=note|Morris (2005) writes, \"Today the Gateway of India has forgotten all its pompous or elegiac meanings and is a place of pleasure, habitually thronged, inside and out, by companionable crowds out for the sea air. The liners no longer come from Londond, and the only boats around the pier are pleasure crafts touting trips around the harbour, or excursions to the Elephanta Caves. It is a merry place, an ice-cream place...\".{{sfn|Jan Morris|2005|p=195}}}} In 2012, the [[Maharashtra Tourism Development Corporation]] moved the Elephanta Festival of Music and Dance from its original location at Elephanta Caves \u2014 where it had been celebrated for 23 years \u2014 to the gateway, due to the increased capacity offered by the venue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tembhekar|first=Chittaranjan|title=Elephanta festival 'moves' to Gateway of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-05/mumbai/31123371_1_elephanta-island-gateway-elephanta-festival|accessdate=30 April 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=5 March 2012|last2=Jaisinghani|first2=Bella|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110175139/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-05/mumbai/31123371_1_elephanta-island-gateway-elephanta-festival|archive-date=10 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The gateway can host 2,000 to 2,500 people, whereas Elephanta Caves could host only 700 to 800.<ref>{{cite news|title=Festival weaves magic|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/festival-weaves-magic/928956/|accessdate=30 November 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=27 March 2012|agency=Express News Service|location=Mumbai}}</ref>\n\nBy the year 2012, the [[Bombay Municipal Corporation]] increased the plaza area around the gateway for pedestrians by restoring the area at a cost of {{INR}}5 crores.<ref name = \"intach\">{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-not-quite-a-getaway/articleshow/12312527.cms?referral=PM | title=Gateway not quite a getaway | date=18 March 2012 | newspaper=Times of India | accessdate=16 August 2019 | author=Lewis, Clara | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110044234/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-not-quite-a-getaway/articleshow/12312527.cms?referral=PM | archive-date=10 January 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> It involved the cutting down of trees, reducing the garden area, replacing toilets and closing the car park. The redevelopment led to a dispute between the [[Indian National Trust for Art and Cultural Heritage]] (INTACH) and the Urban Design Research Institute, and the government was criticised for poor project implementation which critics alleged had failed to conform to the original plans.<ref name = \"intach\"/>\n\nIn January 2014, [[Philips|Philips Lighting India]], in association with the Maharashtra Tourism Development Corporation, undertook the expenditure of {{INR}}2 crores to illuminate the gateway, by installing an LED lighting system with sixteen million shades.<ref name=\"afaqs\">{{cite news | url=https://www.afaqs.com/news/ooh/39792_philips-shows-the-light-at-the-gateway-of-india | title=Philips shows the light at the Gateway of India | date=24 January 2019 | newspaper=Afaqs | accessdate=16 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816171234/https://www.afaqs.com/news/ooh/39792_philips-shows-the-light-at-the-gateway-of-india | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Philips used products from its Philips Color Kinetics and LED street lighting, and did not receive any branding for the illumination project in which 132 light points were created, which were reportedly sixty-percent more energy efficient than the old lighting system.<ref name = \"afaqs\"/> In August 2014, the state Directorate of Archaeology and Museums had proposed conservation of the gateway by the ASI, after noting deterioration caused by [[Salinity|saline deposits]] from the sea.<ref name=\"august2014\"/> An estimate of costs was to be prepared and approved by the ASI. The last such conservation had been undertaken twenty years earlier.<ref name=\"august2014\">{{Cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/consider-chemical-conservation-of-gateway-state-tells-asi/ |title=Consider chemical conservation of Gateway, state tells ASI |last=Rao |first=Srinath Raghvendra |newspaper=The Indian Express |date=11 August 2014 |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714233824/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/consider-chemical-conservation-of-gateway-state-tells-asi/ |archive-date=14 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> An independent study had earlier been conducted at the gateway, between June 2001 and May 2002, aimed at informing future conservation of the monument understanding the degree of colour changes of stones owing to seasonal weather conditions and saturated colour of minerals.{{sfn|Tiwari, L. B.|2005|pp=788-789}} The study found the stones of the monument to appear darker during monsoon than during other seasons while the colour change in the inner portions of the monument rises with variations of seasonal humidity and temperature, given they do not face the sea, rainwater, or sunlight.{{sfn|Tiwari, L. B.|2005|pp=793-794}} It concluded with the finding that the alteration degree and overall colour change in the inner portions are higher than those in the outer portions of the monument.{{sfn|Tiwari, L. B.|2005|p=794}}\n\nIn 2015, the Maharashtra Maritime Board and the Maharashtra Coastal Zone Management Authority approved a proposal to construct a passenger jetty near Apollo Bunder and a promenade between the gateway and the [[Bombay Presidency Radio Club]].<ref name=\"Kulkarni\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-passenger-jetty-promenade-planned-at-apollo-bunder-2128420 |title=Passenger jetty, promenade planned at Apollo Bunder |last=Kulkarni |first=Dhaval |date=25 September 2015 |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis |access-date=20 September 2019 |last2=Shaikh |first2=Ateeq |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209032404/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-passenger-jetty-promenade-planned-at-apollo-bunder-2128420 |archive-date=9 December 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The project was aimed at reducing crowding at the gateway by closing all its jetties and refocusing the location solely as a tourist attraction.<ref name=\"mumbaimirror\">{{Cite news |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/with-jetty-at-apollo-bunder-gateway-to-be-clutter-free/articleshow/45860997.cms |title=With jetty at Apollo Bunder, Gateway to be clutter-free |last=Naik |first=Yogesh |date=13 January 2015 |newspaper=Mumbai Mirror |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe gateway has interested companies and corporate houses such as the [[Tata Group]], the [[RPG Group]] and the [[JSW Group]], who have expressed their wish to maintain the gateway and enhance its facilities.<ref name=\"thetribune2019\"/> This happened after the state government identified 371 heritage sites under its Maharashtra Vaibhav State Protected Monuments Adoption Scheme (MVSPMAS).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-only-2-of-371-maharashtra-s-adopt-a-monument-scheme-a-maha-flop-2612034 | title=Only 2 of 371: Maharashtra's adopt-a-monument scheme a Maha flop | date=6 May 2018 | newspaper=Daily News and Analysis | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Kulkarni, Dhaval | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814065754/https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-only-2-of-371-maharashtra-s-adopt-a-monument-scheme-a-maha-flop-2612034 | archive-date=14 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Under this scheme, companies and corporates can adopt heritage monuments and give out funds for their maintenance, to satisfy their [[corporate social responsibility]].<ref name=\"thetribune2019\"/> The scheme also provides sponsors with the opportunity to generate revenue by selling their rights to feature the heritage monuments in commercials and advertisements. Other revenue-generating opportunities include the sale of entry tickets to the site and charging for the use of facilities.<ref name=\"thetribune2019\">{{cite web | url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/gateway-of-india-other-maha-monuments-up-for-adoption-by-corporates/808216.html | title=Gateway of India, other Maha monuments up for adoption by corporates | publisher=The Tribune | date=26 July 2019 | accessdate=13 August 2019 | author=Kumar, Shiv | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813111617/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/gateway-of-india-other-maha-monuments-up-for-adoption-by-corporates/808216.html | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the Maharashtra state government initiated a plan to restore, clean, and beautify the monument. A project plan was to be prepared in a month.<ref name=\"financial\">{{cite news | url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-to-be-restored-and-beautified/1480340/ | title=Mumbai's iconic Gateway of India to be restored and beautified | date=7 February 2019 | newspaper=The Financial Express | accessdate=13 August 2019 | location=Mumbai | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813103933/https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-to-be-restored-and-beautified/1480340/ | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The state governor, [[C. Vidyasagar Rao]], directed the Bombay Municipal Corporation commissioner and architects to submit a project plan in a month on measures to be taken for the purpose.<ref name=\"asianage\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.asianage.com/metros/mumbai/080219/submit-report-on-preserving-gateway-governor.html |title=Submit report on preserving Gateway: Governor |date=8 February 2019 |newspaper=The Asian Age |access-date=13 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813110443/https://www.asianage.com/metros/mumbai/080219/submit-report-on-preserving-gateway-governor.html |archive-date=13 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"foundation1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/maharashtra-govt-plans-to-beautify-gateway-of-india/article26202879.ece |title=Maharashtra govt plans to beautify Gateway of India  |date=7 February 2019 |newspaper=The Hindu |access-date=13 August 2019}}</ref> In the same month, chemical conservation was proposed by the state archaeology department noting blackening of and algae on stones and surface cracks.  Structural stability audit had last been conducted eight years earlier with plant growth on the monument removed annually.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/plan-to-use-chemicals-to-restore-gateways-sheen/articleshow/67907833.cms | title=Plan to use chemicals to restore Gateway's sheen | date=9 February 2019 | accessdate=24 September 2019 | newspaper=The Times of India | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210150838/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/plan-to-use-chemicals-to-restore-gateways-sheen/articleshow/67907833.cms | archive-date=10 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2019 the state government agreed on a four-stage plan to manage tourists visiting the site. This involved the physical conservation of the monument, the installation of a [[Son et lumi\u00e8re (show)|sound-and-light]] show, the relocation of the anchorage around the monument and a streamlined, ticketed entry system.<ref name=\"TOIlightsound\">{{cite web | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-is-all-set-to-get-some-ground-rules/as68373878.cms | title=Mumbai's iconic Gateway of India is all set to get some ground rules | publisher=Times Travel | date=12 March 2019 | accessdate=13 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828003335/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/mumbais-iconic-gateway-of-india-is-all-set-to-get-some-ground-rules/as68373878.cms | archive-date=28 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The plan followed [[UNESCO]] guidance for protected heritage sites and took into account the views of interested parties, including the Directorate of Museums and Archaeology, which has the monument within its purview; the Mumbai Port Trust, which is entrusted with the land; and the Bombay Municipal Corporation, which controls the location. The task of coming up with a suitable management plan was delegated to architects.<ref name=\"DNAReport\">{{cite web | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-mumbai-light-sound-show-low-entry-fee-to-push-gateway-tourism-2728505 | title=Mumbai: Light-&-sound show, low entry fee to push Gateway tourism | newspaper=Daily News and Analysis | date=11 March 2019 | accessdate=13 August 2019 | author=Kulkarni, Dhaval | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813113038/https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-mumbai-light-sound-show-low-entry-fee-to-push-gateway-tourism-2728505 | archive-date=13 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, [[Snapchat]] extended its Landmarker features to the gateway by which users can superimpose [[augmented reality]] experiences on top of their pictures of the gateway.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/snapchat-landmarkers-india-monuments-gateway-of-india-taj-mahal-lens-studio-2-1-2091072 | title=Snapchat's Landmarkers Feature Enters India, Lens Studio 2.1 Released With New Templates | date=27 August 2019 | newspaper=NDTV Gadgets 360.com | accessdate=29 August 2019 | author=Singh, Jagmeet | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828112129/https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/snapchat-landmarkers-india-monuments-gateway-of-india-taj-mahal-lens-studio-2-1-2091072 | archive-date=28 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Events and incidents==\n[[File:3 December 2008 Gateway protest march 5.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Solidarity march at the gateway premises, in the aftermath of the 2008 Mumbai terror attacks]]\nThe gateway was the location of a [[25 August 2003 Mumbai bombings|terror attack on 25 August 2003]], when there was a bomb blast in front of it.<ref name=\"vanityfair\"/> The force of the explosion, from a bomb in a taxi parked near the Taj Mahal hotel, reportedly threw bystanders into the sea.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|title=2003: Bombay rocked by twin car bombs|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/25/newsid_3921000/3921475.stm|date=25 August 2003|accessdate=16 April 2012|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410202413/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/25/newsid_3921000/3921475.stm|archivedate=10 April 2012}}</ref> On 13 August 2005, a mentally unstable man stabbed two young girls from [[Manipur]] at the gateway premises.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maniac stabs girl to death at Gateway|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Maniac-stabs-girl-to-death-at-Gateway/articleshow/1200458.cms|accessdate=14 August 2005|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 August 2005|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118121653/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Maniac-stabs-girl-to-death-at-Gateway/articleshow/1200458.cms|archivedate=18 January 2018}}</ref> On New Year's Eve, 2007 a woman was groped by a mob at the gateway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gateway groping shocks Mumbai|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-groping-shocks-Mumbai/articleshow/1028075.cms|accessdate=3 January 2007|newspaper=The Times of India|date=3 January 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129014412/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Gateway-groping-shocks-Mumbai/articleshow/1028075.cms|archivedate=29 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|November 2008 Mumbai terror attacks]], which targeted the Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel opposite to the gateway, among other locations, crowds of people including news television reporters and cameramen congregated at the gateway premises.<ref name=\"vanityfair\">{{cite news | url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/11/taj-hotel-siege-200911 | title=Anatomy of a Siege | date=30 September 2009 | newspaper=Vanity Fair | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Brenner, Marie | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713232325/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/11/taj-hotel-siege-200911 | archive-date=13 July 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/asia/after-the-terrorist-attacks-the-gateway-to-india-is-open-to-the-world-8975051.html | title=After the terrorist attacks: The gateway to India is open to the world | date=30 November 2013 | newspaper=Independent | accessdate=14 August 2019 | author=Leadbeater, Chris | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814074444/https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/asia/after-the-terrorist-attacks-the-gateway-to-india-is-open-to-the-world-8975051.html | archive-date=14 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, public access to the area around was restricted.<ref name = \"intach\"/> Fearing further attacks on the gateway and on the Elephanta caves, the state government proposed the closure of all of the jetties at the gateway and their replacement with two new piers, to be built near the Bombay Presidency Radio Club.<ref name=dna09>{{cite news|title=5 jetties may be shut|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_5-jetties-may-be-shut_1225849|accessdate=30 April 2012|newspaper=Daily News and Analysis|date=29 January 2009}}</ref> In response to the terror attacks a solidarity march was held at the gateway premises on 3 December 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1864035,00.html |title=A Rally in Mumbai: \"Remember 26-11!\" |last=Tharoor |first=Ishaan |date=3 December 2008 |newspaper= Time |access-date=20 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202212930/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1864035,00.html |archive-date=2 December 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Show-of-solidarity-at-Gateway-of-India/articleshow/3788910.cms |title=Show of solidarity at Gateway of India |date=3 December 2008 |newspaper=Times of India |access-date=20 September 2019 |agency=PTI}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, protests were organised at the premises in the wake of the [[Pulwama attack]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pulwama-attack-mumbaikars-show-solidarity-with-crpf-martyrs-119021601097_1.html |title=Pulwama attack: Mumbaikars show solidarity with CRPF martyrs |date=16 February 2019 |newspaper=Business Standard |access-date=20 September 2019 |agency=PTI |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216212215/https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pulwama-attack-mumbaikars-show-solidarity-with-crpf-martyrs-119021601097_1.html |archive-date=16 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2020, the gateway became a site of spontaneous protests that commenced overnight, under the name of \"Occupy Gateway\", in the aftermath of the [[2020 Jawaharlal Nehru University attack|attack on Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/948950/at-occupygateway-mumbai-citizens-have-been-protesting-in-solidarity-with-jnu-for-over-16-hours | title=At #OccupyGateway, Mumbai citizens have been protesting in solidarity with JNU for over 16 hours | work=Scroll | date=6 January 2020 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Johari, Aarefa | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218121250/https://scroll.in/article/948950/at-occupygateway-mumbai-citizens-have-been-protesting-in-solidarity-with-jnu-for-over-16-hours | archive-date=18 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Protestors were later relocated from the gateway premises to [[Azad Maidan]] in Mumbai to ease the movement of traffic and people.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/mumbai-protest-protesters-evicted-from-gateway-of-india-and-relocated-to-azad-maidan/article30501355.ece | title=Mumbai protest: Protesters evicted from Gateway of India and relocated to Azad Maidan | work=Hindustan Times | date=7 January 2020 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Sheth, Himani | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108165821/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/mumbai-protest-protesters-evicted-from-gateway-of-india-and-relocated-to-azad-maidan/article30501355.ece | archive-date=8 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/jnu-violence-protestors-relocated-from-gateway-of-india-to-azad-maidan-to-avoid-inconvenience-to-citizens-claims-mumbai-police-7870561.html | title=JNU violence: Protestors 'relocated' from Gateway of India to Azad Maidan to avoid inconvenience to citizens, claims Mumbai Police | work=Firstpost | date=7 January 2020 | agency=Press Trust of India | accessdate=18 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108214751/https://www.firstpost.com/india/jnu-violence-protestors-relocated-from-gateway-of-india-to-azad-maidan-to-avoid-inconvenience-to-citizens-claims-mumbai-police-7870561.html | archive-date=8 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:The Apollo Bunder- the Gate of India.jpg|Apollo Bunder, in 1905, with the location where the gateway stands today\nFile:Gateway of india a.jpg|Pigeons on the gateway grounds\nFile:Gateway of India aerial view.jpg|Aerial view of the gateway, with its erstwhile gardened esplanade\nFile:India Mumbai Victor Grigas 2011-7.jpg|''[[Jali]]'' work on the arches\nFile:Gateway of India - 11 (Friar's Balsam Flickr).jpg|Floral motifs, as seen on the gateway\nFile:Gateway of India - turret.jpg|Close-up of a turret\nFile:Gateway of india's look in evening.jpg|The gateway, lit up in the evening\nFile:Arch of Gateway of India.jpg|Internal view of the dome, with ''[[muqarnas]]'' designs\nFile:Beating Retreat and Tattoo ceremony at Gateway of India, 2018 (9).jpg|Beating the Retreat and Tattoo Ceremony at the gateway, on [[Navy Day (India)|Navy Day]] in 2018\nFile:Gateway of India , Hotel Taj and ,Oberoi Hotels , Mumbai, Mahrashtra, India.jpg|The gateway, as seen with the Taj Mahal Palace and Tower Hotel\nFile:A photographer advertising his sevices at the Gateway of India (18566738741).jpg|Photographer offering services, in the vicinity of the gateway\nFile:Indian farmers at Gateway of India.png|Farmers engaged in an awareness campaign at the gateway\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua|30em}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes and news reports===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Books and journals===\n{{Refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book|ref = {{harvid|Civic Affairs|1961}}|title=Civic Affairs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aOkmAQAAIAAJ|year=1961|publisher=P. C. Kapoor at the Citizen Press}}\n* {{cite book|ref = {{harvid|Bombay Civic Journal|1975}}|title=The Bombay Civic Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N4zRyapZSRMC|year=1975|publisher=Municipal Corporation of Greater Bombay}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=A. K. Bag|title=History of Technology in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lDshAQAAIAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Indian National Science Academy}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Ajoy Kumar Sen|title=Tourism in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ugbAAAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Modern Book Agency}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Anthony Hewitt|title=Corridors of Time: Distant Footsteps Through the Empire 1914-1948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GHduAAAAMAAJ|year=1993|publisher=Pentland|isbn=978-1-85821-092-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=B.K. Chaturvedi|title=Tourist Centers Of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QrLcFkhRZPYC|year=2002|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd.|isbn=978-81-7182-137-2}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=B. Karunakar|title=Corporate Champions: Excellent Companies of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aqKoDwAAQBAJ|date=7 December 2011|publisher=SAGE Publishing India|isbn=978-81-321-1919-7}}\n* {{cite journal | ref=harv|title=Religion and identity in India's heritage tourism | author=Bandyopadhyay, Ranjan | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | year=2008 | volume=35 | issue=3 | pages=790\u2013808 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2008.06.004 |display-authors=et al.}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Berlitz|title=Berlitz Pocket Guide India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0StHDwAAQBAJ|date=1 August 2017|publisher=Apa Publications|isbn=978-1-78573-058-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Bombay State Road Transport Corporation|title=State Transport Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xRbWAAAAMAAJ|volume=9|year=1958}}\n* {{Britannica|72526|Mumbai - Cultural Life|Chakravarthi Raghavan}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Charles Edward Trevelyan|title=On the Education of the People of India|url=https://archive.org/details/oneducationpeop00trevgoog|year=1838|publisher=Longman, Orme, Brown, Green & Longmans|author-link=Sir Charles Trevelyan, 1st Baronet}}\n* {